1
00:00:34,096 --> 00:00:38,520
My name is Dale Kerrigan,
and this is my story.

2
00:00:38,592 --> 00:00:41,932
<i>Our family lives at 3 Highview Crescent,
Coolaroo.</i>

3
00:00:42,086 --> 00:00:44,924
<i>Dad bought this place
15 years ago for a steal.</i>

4
00:00:45,063 --> 00:00:48,363
<i>As the real estate agent
said, "Location, location, location."</i>

5
00:00:48,548 --> 00:00:50,243
<i>And we're right next door
to the airport.</i>

6
00:00:51,350 --> 00:00:54,389
<i>It will be very convenient
if we ever have to fly one day.</i>

7
00:00:57,944 --> 00:01:00,520
<i>Dad still can't work out
how he got it so cheap.</i>

8
00:01:00,590 --> 00:01:03,775
<i>It's worth almost as much today
as when we bought it.</i>

9
00:01:03,842 --> 00:01:06,701
<i>Our street was going to be the heart
of a major housing development.</i>

10
00:01:06,775 --> 00:01:08,939
<i>But it never got up.</i>

11
00:01:09,007 --> 00:01:12,702
<i>They reckon the planes put people off.
Them and the power lines.</i>

12
00:01:12,769 --> 00:01:16,073
<i>Not Dad. He reckons power lines
are a reminder...</i>

13
00:01:16,148 --> 00:01:18,594
<i>of man's ability
to generate electricity.</i>

14
00:01:18,667 --> 00:01:23,352
<i>He's always saying
great things like that.
That's why we love him so much.</i>

15
00:01:23,417 --> 00:01:26,472
<i>Dad is the backbone
of the Kerrigan family.</i>

16
00:01:26,542 --> 00:01:29,249
<i>He made our billiard table.</i>

17
00:01:29,316 --> 00:01:31,577
Shot, Dale.

18
00:01:31,643 --> 00:01:35,524
<i>In fact, he's built half this house.
He's always planning extensions.</i>

19
00:01:35,596 --> 00:01:37,444
I reckon we need a patio.

20
00:01:37,509 --> 00:01:40,498
Oh, darl, how about we finish
the back room first?

21
00:01:40,570 --> 00:01:43,407
No, I'm waiting
on some cheap siding.

22
00:01:43,472 --> 00:01:45,352
I reckon we give
the patio another go.

23
00:01:45,416 --> 00:01:49,144
<i>Dad is a tow truck driver.
One of the best in the game.</i>

24
00:01:49,210 --> 00:01:51,656
<i>He takes great pride
in his work.</i>

25
00:01:51,729 --> 00:01:54,338
<i>And he comes home
with so many stories.</i>

26
00:01:54,406 --> 00:01:56,765
You see, the car was wrapped
around the pole,

27
00:01:56,830 --> 00:01:59,601
so I said, " Why not hook the chain
on the back axle?"

28
00:01:59,667 --> 00:02:01,515
See, no one
had thought of that.

29
00:02:01,580 --> 00:02:05,363
<i>If Dad is the backbone,
Mum is the other bones. All of them.</i>

30
00:02:05,438 --> 00:02:07,502
<i>She keeps
the family together.</i>

31
00:02:07,574 --> 00:02:09,954
<i>Dad adores Mum,
and Mum adores him.</i>

32
00:02:10,029 --> 00:02:13,312
<i>They met at the greyhounds one night,
and it was love at first sight.</i>

33
00:02:13,377 --> 00:02:16,660
<i>Mum just loves craft.
And she can pretty up
just about anything.</i>

34
00:02:16,724 --> 00:02:18,572
How did you do that?

35
00:02:18,637 --> 00:02:22,517
- Spray can and stencil, darl.
That's all you need.
- You could sell that.

36
00:02:22,591 --> 00:02:24,754
<i>Dad always reckons
Mum could open a shop,</i>

37
00:02:24,822 --> 00:02:27,626
<i>but she has a good part-time job
in the office at Sunbeam.</i>

38
00:02:27,691 --> 00:02:30,267
<i>Dad reckons Mum is
the greatest cook on Earth.</i>

39
00:02:30,338 --> 00:02:33,077
- What do you call that, darl?
- Sponge cake.

40
00:02:33,143 --> 00:02:36,035
Beautiful. And what's
that stuff on top?

41
00:02:36,108 --> 00:02:39,326
- Icing sugar.
- How is it, kids?

42
00:02:39,392 --> 00:02:42,610
And why would you want
to go out to a restaurant...

43
00:02:42,676 --> 00:02:45,002
when this keeps coming up
night after night?

44
00:02:45,067 --> 00:02:47,230
<i>I have two brothers
and a sister, all older than me.</i>

45
00:02:47,299 --> 00:02:51,561
<i>Steve is an apprentice mechanic,
but he spends most of his time
reading the Trading Post.</i>

46
00:02:51,635 --> 00:02:53,700
<i>He just loves
buying and trading.</i>

47
00:02:53,771 --> 00:02:55,934
Dad, ergonomic chairs.
Four of them.

48
00:02:56,003 --> 00:02:58,199
- What does he want?
- One-eighty.

49
00:02:58,266 --> 00:03:00,114
He's dreaming.

50
00:03:00,179 --> 00:03:02,886
<i>Him and Dad
really know bargains.</i>

51
00:03:02,953 --> 00:03:06,617
<i>Steve is also an ideas man.
That's why Dad calls him the ideas man.</i>

52
00:03:06,683 --> 00:03:08,531
<i>He has lots of ideas.</i>

53
00:03:08,596 --> 00:03:11,846
It's a motorcycle helmet
with a built-in brake light.

54
00:03:11,912 --> 00:03:14,749
You are an ideas man, Steve.

55
00:03:14,813 --> 00:03:17,259
<i>Dad thinks all of us
are tremendous,</i>

56
00:03:17,332 --> 00:03:19,657
<i>but I guess it's no secret
that Tracey's his favorite.</i>

57
00:03:19,723 --> 00:03:21,571
How do I look, Dad?

58
00:03:21,636 --> 00:03:23,569
<i>Dad just loves her.</i>

59
00:03:23,570 --> 00:03:26,252
You look beautiful.

60
00:03:26,570 --> 00:03:27,555
Thanks, Dad.

61
00:03:27,630 --> 00:03:31,989
<i>Tracey's the only girl in the family,
apart from Mum and Gran.</i>

62
00:03:32,062 --> 00:03:34,834
<i>Tracey constantly
gave Dad proud moments.</i>

63
00:03:34,899 --> 00:03:38,051
<i>Once she was
on "The Price Is Right".</i>

64
00:03:38,119 --> 00:03:40,977
<i>It was such
an exciting afternoon for us.</i>

65
00:03:41,052 --> 00:03:42,900
Swap them around.

66
00:03:42,965 --> 00:03:45,954
<i>None of us could actually
believe it was Tracey up there
with Larry Emdier.</i>

67
00:03:46,025 --> 00:03:49,841
$45,000 worth of prizes.
The luggage needs to be more than 640.

68
00:03:49,915 --> 00:03:53,067
It needs to be less
than 740.

69
00:03:53,135 --> 00:03:55,428
<i>She almost won the lot.</i>

70
00:03:57,276 --> 00:03:59,147
<i>If only she'd known
the price of the luggage.</i>

71
00:03:59,286 --> 00:04:01,244
I'm so sorry about that.

72
00:04:01,860 --> 00:04:04,206
<i>But she still managed to come home
with a tumble dryer and drill set.</i>

73
00:04:04,275 --> 00:04:09,526
<i>She is the only member of the Kerrigan
family who'd had a college education.</i>

74
00:04:09,600 --> 00:04:13,263
<i>Dad reckons the day she graduated
as a fully-qualified hairdresser...</i>

75
00:04:13,330 --> 00:04:15,558
<i>was about
the proudest day of his life.</i>

76
00:04:15,625 --> 00:04:18,429
<i>I knew he thought
about that... a lot.</i>

77
00:04:18,494 --> 00:04:20,820
<i>There were only two places
he did his thinking--</i>

78
00:04:20,886 --> 00:04:24,962
<i>in the poolroom and out the back,
looking up at the power lines.</i>

79
00:04:25,825 --> 00:04:28,725
<i>Yep, Dad's a real thinker.</i>

80
00:04:27,759 --> 00:04:32,476
<i>But the proudest day
was the day she got married
to this nice guy called Con.</i>

81
00:04:32,541 --> 00:04:35,693
<i>He is an accountant,
but also a fanatical kickboxer.</i>

82
00:04:35,761 --> 00:04:38,087
<i>Now Tracey's
taken up kickboxing too.</i>

83
00:04:38,153 --> 00:04:40,566
<i>Dad could not get
the smile off his face.</i>

84
00:04:40,639 --> 00:04:42,965
<i>And he gave a speech
that brought the house down.</i>

85
00:04:43,031 --> 00:04:45,890
Now, as the bride's parents,
I don't mind paying for the wedding,

86
00:04:45,963 --> 00:04:48,703
but could you please stop busting
all them plates?

87
00:04:48,769 --> 00:04:51,889
That being
a Greek custom and all.

88
00:04:52,913 --> 00:04:54,848
I suppose, as a father,

89
00:04:54,923 --> 00:04:57,879
you'd like your daughter
to marry one of your own.

90
00:04:57,951 --> 00:05:01,734
And let's not beat around the bush.
The Greeks have a reputation.

91
00:05:01,809 --> 00:05:04,701
<i>At first, the Petropoulouses
thought he was having a go at them.</i>

92
00:05:04,774 --> 00:05:07,100
<i>But Dad was just saying
how much he thought of Con.</i>

93
00:05:07,165 --> 00:05:10,600
I never thought anyone
could love our Trace...

94
00:05:10,672 --> 00:05:12,770
as much as me,
Sal and the boys.

95
00:05:12,840 --> 00:05:15,547
But there is
another person. Con.

96
00:05:17,242 --> 00:05:19,280
Smart, polite,
fit as a fiddle.

97
00:05:19,315 --> 00:05:23,509
And anyone who loves our Trace
as much as us deserves our love.

98
00:05:23,654 --> 00:05:27,452
So we love you, Con.
We love you.

99
00:05:28,528 --> 00:05:29,413
Thank you, and, uh,

100
00:05:29,482 --> 00:05:32,103
"Kalispera".

101
00:05:32,266 --> 00:05:34,041
That's "Good evening."

102
00:05:37,935 --> 00:05:41,570
<i>We'd had many top nights,
but this was the most top.</i>

103
00:05:42,330 --> 00:05:44,104
<i>Pity my oldest brother
couldn't be there.</i>

104
00:05:44,256 --> 00:05:47,016
<i>His name's Wayne.
He's in jail.</i>

105
00:05:47,463 --> 00:05:49,847
<i>Eight years
for armed robbery.</i>

106
00:05:50,086 --> 00:05:53,941
<i>Many people call him the black sheep
of the family. But not Mum and Dad.</i>

107
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,019
<i>He got caught up with the wrong crowd.
He didn't mean to rob the gas station.</i>

108
00:05:57,152 --> 00:06:01,002
<i>Now he's sorry. With good behavior,
he'll be out in a couple of years.</i>

109
00:06:01,200 --> 00:06:03,074
<i>I visit him every Friday.</i>

110
00:06:03,557 --> 00:06:05,410
- How's Mum?
- Good.

111
00:06:07,091 --> 00:06:09,031
- How's Dad?
- Good.

112
00:06:11,235 --> 00:06:13,306
- How's Trace?
- Good.

113
00:06:16,323 --> 00:06:18,361
- How are you?
- Good.

114
00:06:20,700 --> 00:06:23,236
- How's Dave?
- He's all right.

115
00:06:24,261 --> 00:06:25,347
Good.

116
00:06:25,830 --> 00:06:29,045
<i>Even though he's the oldest
and I'm the youngest, we get on great.</i>

117
00:06:29,182 --> 00:06:31,107
<i>We can just chat for hours.</i>

118
00:06:32,127 --> 00:06:34,677
Thanks for coming down.

119
00:06:34,748 --> 00:06:37,266
- You want some chewy?
- No.

120
00:06:37,337 --> 00:06:41,359
<i>So, as you can see,
our family is very close-knit.</i>

121
00:06:41,430 --> 00:06:43,948
<i>We also have pets.
Four greyhounds.</i>

122
00:06:44,019 --> 00:06:45,806
<i>Banshee,</i>

123
00:06:45,873 --> 00:06:47,628
<i>Starflash,</i>

124
00:06:47,696 --> 00:06:50,562
<i>Trailblazer and Coco.</i>

125
00:06:50,637 --> 00:06:54,082
<i>Coco is the best,
most successful Dad has ever had.</i>

126
00:06:54,154 --> 00:06:57,533
<i>She picked up two firsts
in the country and a third in town.</i>

127
00:06:57,607 --> 00:06:59,777
<i>Dad feeds them every morning
in big bowls...</i>

128
00:06:59,844 --> 00:07:02,330
<i>that Steve made out
of tractor hubcaps.</i>

129
00:07:02,403 --> 00:07:05,270
<i>They are good dogs. Good to Dad.
And Dad is good to them.</i>

130
00:07:05,344 --> 00:07:09,116
<i>All of them are descended
from his first dog, Red Rocket.</i>

131
00:07:09,181 --> 00:07:13,072
<i>Dad never stops marveling
at the beauty of the greyhound.</i>

132
00:07:13,145 --> 00:07:15,598
<i>In fact, he doesn't even
race them for the money.</i>

133
00:07:15,670 --> 00:07:19,050
<i>He reckons they are noble animals.
Skinny and sleek...</i>

134
00:07:19,123 --> 00:07:20,977
<i>and have a beautiful snout.</i>

135
00:07:21,042 --> 00:07:25,162
<i>Another thing Dad loves
is his boat. Sea Lady.</i>

136
00:07:25,230 --> 00:07:28,042
<i>He cleans it every Saturday
with something else Steve built.</i>

137
00:07:28,107 --> 00:07:30,080
<i>It's a brush
with a hose in it.</i>

138
00:07:30,153 --> 00:07:32,834
<i>Dad never stops marveling
at Steve's ideas.</i>

139
00:07:32,903 --> 00:07:35,137
He's a ideas man, Steve.

140
00:07:35,204 --> 00:07:37,657
<i>Steve gave it to Dad
for Father's Day.</i>

141
00:07:37,730 --> 00:07:41,436
<i>That's something our family
prides itself on. Presents.</i>

142
00:07:41,503 --> 00:07:44,086
<i>Even though none of us
have a real lot of money,</i>

143
00:07:44,157 --> 00:07:46,358
<i>we love giving
each other presents.</i>

144
00:07:46,426 --> 00:07:49,490
- He got a rod and reel from Trace.
- A rod and reel.

145
00:07:49,560 --> 00:07:51,729
- I gave him a new muzzle.
- A muzzle.

146
00:07:51,797 --> 00:07:54,129
<i>Wayne sent him an ashtray
he'd made in prison shop.</i>

147
00:07:54,195 --> 00:07:56,943
An ashtray?
But I don't smoke.

148
00:07:57,009 --> 00:08:01,794
<i>And Mum, well, Mum got him a big German
beer mug from Franklin Mint.</i>

149
00:08:01,868 --> 00:08:05,607
<i>Dad couldn't believe his eyes. It was
too good to even drink beer out of.</i>

150
00:08:05,672 --> 00:08:07,525
I'd like
to do pottery.

151
00:08:07,590 --> 00:08:09,923
Oh, you should.
You'd be good at it.

152
00:08:09,989 --> 00:08:13,273
This is going straight
to the poolroom.

153
00:08:13,275 --> 00:08:15,831
<i>All Dad's most prized possessions
are in the poolroom.</i>

154
00:08:15,900 --> 00:08:19,289
<i>All his mementos and things
that remind him of something special.</i>

155
00:08:19,381 --> 00:08:22,230
<i>So by him saying it was going straight
to the poolroom...</i>

156
00:08:22,297 --> 00:08:24,084
<i>meant he thought
it was special.</i>

157
00:08:24,151 --> 00:08:27,280
That is a collector's item.

158
00:08:27,349 --> 00:08:30,990
This has been
the best Father's Day ever.

159
00:08:31,058 --> 00:08:32,911
<i>Of course there
were ups and downs.</i>

160
00:08:32,976 --> 00:08:35,363
<i>Wayne being in jail
was an example of a down.</i>

161
00:08:35,438 --> 00:08:38,501
<i>But, all in all,
3 Highview Crescent was a happy home.</i>

162
00:08:38,571 --> 00:08:40,479
<i>Dad called it his castle.</i>

163
00:08:40,585 --> 00:08:42,917
<i>But one day in June,</i>

164
00:08:42,983 --> 00:08:45,152
<i>a knock at the door
was to change all that.</i>

165
00:08:45,221 --> 00:08:47,074
- Yeah?
- Mr. Darryl Kerrigan?

166
00:08:47,139 --> 00:08:50,235
- Yeah?
- John Clifton.
I'm from the local council.

167
00:08:50,304 --> 00:08:52,157
- Is this about the dogs?
- No.

168
00:08:52,222 --> 00:08:54,075
- The aerial? The extensions?
- No.

169
00:08:54,141 --> 00:08:58,871
Look, if this is about
my truck on the nature strip,
I've had it out with you guys.

170
00:08:58,936 --> 00:09:02,446
No, I'm a valuer
with the local council.
I'm here to do a land valuation.

171
00:09:02,517 --> 00:09:05,383
- What for?
- Well, all properties
get valued from time to time.

172
00:09:05,458 --> 00:09:08,652
So, you'd be able
to give me a value on this place?

173
00:09:08,720 --> 00:09:11,564
- That's my job.
- That'd be good.

174
00:09:11,628 --> 00:09:15,106
- Do you want me
to show you around?
- If you wouldn't mind.

175
00:09:15,178 --> 00:09:18,558
Oh, not at all.
Be pleased to.

176
00:09:18,630 --> 00:09:22,685
Because, between you and me,
I reckon the values around here are--

177
00:09:26,367 --> 00:09:29,942
As you can see,
I've put a fair bit of work into it.

178
00:09:30,012 --> 00:09:32,344
Would you like me to point out
the features as we go along?

179
00:09:32,409 --> 00:09:34,775
- If you wouldn't mind.
- You see that lace up there?

180
00:09:34,840 --> 00:09:37,619
- Yeah?
- Fake. Plastic.

181
00:09:37,685 --> 00:09:40,999
Gives the place
a Victoriana feel.

182
00:09:41,074 --> 00:09:44,006
The chimney? Fake too.

183
00:09:44,079 --> 00:09:45,932
Why is it there?

184
00:09:45,997 --> 00:09:49,955
Charm. Adds a bit of charm.
Look at the size of that aerial.

185
00:09:50,025 --> 00:09:53,284
That's a big aerial.
What do you think? Add a bit of value?

186
00:09:53,350 --> 00:09:56,162
- Hard to say. Yeah.
- Yeah.

187
00:09:56,227 --> 00:09:58,975
You can overcapitalize,
can't you?

188
00:09:59,042 --> 00:10:01,374
But it's a huge aerial.

189
00:10:06,043 --> 00:10:09,968
And this is my backyard.

190
00:10:14,163 --> 00:10:16,845
- Shuttle. From Melbourne to Sidney.

191
00:10:16,914 --> 00:10:20,227
- How close are you
to the end of the runway?
- Ah, just over the fence.

192
00:10:22,636 --> 00:10:25,481
- Is that the runway there?
- Yeah.

193
00:10:25,546 --> 00:10:28,161
- There?
- Yeah.

194
00:10:28,230 --> 00:10:29,463
Beautiful machines.

195
00:10:29,773 --> 00:10:32,772
Sometimes you think
they're gonna land right on top of you.

196
00:10:33,796 --> 00:10:36,431
Freaks the dogs, though.
Greyhounds.

197
00:10:36,704 --> 00:10:38,971
Large kennel.

198
00:10:39,517 --> 00:10:42,514
Well, originally, it was a tree house
when the kids were growing up.

199
00:10:42,585 --> 00:10:44,973
I was thinking of turning it
into another room.

200
00:10:45,047 --> 00:10:46,806
- But the county said no.
- Ah.

201
00:10:46,942 --> 00:10:50,717
Now, here back, all landfill.
Not allowed to build there.

202
00:10:50,878 --> 00:10:54,156
- Has the soil been tested?
- Oh, yeah.

203
00:10:54,224 --> 00:10:57,123
Nothing too serious
in there.

204
00:10:57,197 --> 00:11:00,096
What do you know
about lead?

205
00:11:03,303 --> 00:11:06,649
Oh, this is
beautiful, darl.

206
00:11:06,724 --> 00:11:09,471
- What do you call these things again?
- Meat loaf.

207
00:11:09,537 --> 00:11:11,390
Everybody cooks
meat loaf, darl.

208
00:11:11,456 --> 00:11:13,363
Yeah, but it's
what you do with them.

209
00:11:13,438 --> 00:11:16,883
Mum reckons the trick is you
don't use minced meat.
She gets topside and crushes it.

210
00:11:16,954 --> 00:11:18,862
Is that right, darl?
Well, it shows.

211
00:11:18,936 --> 00:11:21,106
She gets silverside
and she'll crush that too.

212
00:11:21,175 --> 00:11:24,271
Dad, a guy's selling
a pair of jousting sticks.

213
00:11:24,339 --> 00:11:27,021
Jousting sticks?
What does he want for them?

214
00:11:27,089 --> 00:11:30,185
- Make us an offer.
- Darl, what do you want
with jousting sticks?

215
00:11:30,255 --> 00:11:33,154
Oh, I don't know. But I reckon they
wouldn't come up all that often.

216
00:11:33,228 --> 00:11:36,869
But they're jousting sticks.
What would anyone want
with jousting sticks?

217
00:11:36,935 --> 00:11:40,129
Well, if you get them
for half price, it's a bargain.

218
00:11:40,197 --> 00:11:42,051
- Give him a call?
- Yeah.

219
00:11:44,034 --> 00:11:47,642
I'll be interested to see
this fella's valuation.

220
00:11:47,710 --> 00:11:50,359
- Are you thinking
of selling, Dad?
- Oh, no, mate, no.

221
00:11:50,428 --> 00:11:52,695
But it would be nice to know
what we're sitting on here.

222
00:11:52,762 --> 00:11:54,189
Clay.

223
00:11:54,265 --> 00:11:56,596
No, mate.
The value of the house.

224
00:11:56,662 --> 00:12:01,481
You know, it's odd, because
Farouk reckoned he had
some bloke around as well.

225
00:12:01,554 --> 00:12:04,072
Must've been doing
the whole street.

226
00:12:04,143 --> 00:12:06,476
- Maybe the market's on the move.
- Here?

227
00:12:06,542 --> 00:12:08,611
Dad? Four-fifty.

228
00:12:08,683 --> 00:12:11,942
For jousting sticks?
Tell him he's dreaming.

229
00:12:12,009 --> 00:12:13,981
How much is a jousting stick worth,
Dad?

230
00:12:14,055 --> 00:12:16,866
Well, it couldn't be more
than 250.

231
00:12:16,932 --> 00:12:20,376
- Depending on the condition.
- When do we find out?

232
00:12:20,448 --> 00:12:24,023
Well, we should have the official notice
in a couple of weeks.

233
00:12:24,094 --> 00:12:25,979
But just quietly,

234
00:12:26,044 --> 00:12:30,350
I reckon we could be in
for a little surprise.

235
00:12:30,455 --> 00:12:33,267
Compulsorily acquired.

236
00:12:34,772 --> 00:12:37,104
Compulsorily acquired.

237
00:12:38,608 --> 00:12:41,737
You know what this means,
don't you?

238
00:12:41,805 --> 00:12:46,470
- They're acquiring it compulsorily.
- It must be a mistake.

239
00:12:46,537 --> 00:12:49,350
They're gonna take our place,
and we don't get a say in it.

240
00:12:49,415 --> 00:12:53,601
- Well, how can they do that?
- I don't know. 70,000 bucks.

241
00:12:53,666 --> 00:12:55,639
Who the hell
is Air Link?

242
00:12:55,712 --> 00:12:59,669
- Dad, a guy's selling seven coolers.
- Hang on, Steve.

243
00:12:59,741 --> 00:13:01,910
What's that?
Is this about Wayne?

244
00:13:01,979 --> 00:13:04,343
No, no. Look.

245
00:13:04,409 --> 00:13:06,513
What do you make
of that?

246
00:13:08,820 --> 00:13:12,559
Jesus. This is
a kick-out notice.

247
00:13:12,626 --> 00:13:16,419
I'll get it. I'll get it.

248
00:13:21,193 --> 00:13:23,678
- Ah, good day, Farouk.
- Hello, Mr. Kerrigan.

249
00:13:23,750 --> 00:13:25,756
Can you read to me something,
please, I get today?

250
00:13:25,829 --> 00:13:28,161
Yeah, sure, mate,
but I'm a bit busy at the moment.

251
00:13:28,227 --> 00:13:31,072
Can I-- Can I come--

252
00:13:31,136 --> 00:13:34,679
- Shit. You got one too.
- Got what?

253
00:13:34,749 --> 00:13:38,062
What the hell
is going on?

254
00:13:38,137 --> 00:13:41,614
Jesus Christ.
Jack!

255
00:13:51,757 --> 00:13:54,406
Jack, it's Darryl, mate.

256
00:14:00,038 --> 00:14:03,385
Someone is going
to take me house, Darryl.

257
00:14:10,173 --> 00:14:14,097
- Mr. Kerrigan.
- Yeah. Yeah.

258
00:14:16,375 --> 00:14:18,380
Mr. Kerrigan--

259
00:14:18,454 --> 00:14:21,614
Darryl, this is
a compulsory acquisition.

260
00:14:21,683 --> 00:14:23,720
Yeah.

261
00:14:23,792 --> 00:14:27,138
Mr. Kerrigan,
the airport is expanding.

262
00:14:27,213 --> 00:14:29,893
They're setting up one of the largest
freight-handling facilities...

263
00:14:29,963 --> 00:14:33,222
in the Southern Hemisphere,
and they need a great deal of space.

264
00:14:33,288 --> 00:14:35,674
Yeah.

265
00:14:35,750 --> 00:14:40,088
And your house...
is on that space.

266
00:14:40,162 --> 00:14:42,615
Yeah. Yeah,my house.

267
00:14:42,687 --> 00:14:45,019
That's right. Your house.

268
00:14:45,085 --> 00:14:47,122
That's why
you'll be duly compensated.

269
00:14:47,195 --> 00:14:51,250
No. No, you've missed the point.
I'm not interested in compensation.

270
00:14:51,319 --> 00:14:53,521
I don't wanna go.

271
00:14:53,589 --> 00:14:55,660
Under the laws
of compulsory acquisition--

272
00:14:55,731 --> 00:14:59,241
and I don't necessarily
agree with those laws--

273
00:14:59,311 --> 00:15:01,698
I can understand
the pain and trouble--

274
00:15:01,774 --> 00:15:04,260
Would you stop pretending
to be on my side?

275
00:15:05,769 --> 00:15:08,320
All right, Mr. Kerrigan,
I'll state this simply.

276
00:15:08,392 --> 00:15:10,246
There is
an ironclad agreement...

277
00:15:10,311 --> 00:15:13,024
between federal, state
and local governments
and the Airports Commission.

278
00:15:13,091 --> 00:15:14,944
Yeah?

279
00:15:15,009 --> 00:15:19,228
Well, where's the agreement
with Darryl Kerrigan,
3 Highview Crescent, Coolaroo?

280
00:15:19,294 --> 00:15:22,673
Where'sthat agreement?

281
00:15:22,746 --> 00:15:26,834
It's not gonna happen.

282
00:16:28,862 --> 00:16:31,315
I don't know, Darryl.
This isn't my area.

283
00:16:31,387 --> 00:16:34,451
What do you mean this is not your area?
This is law.

284
00:16:34,521 --> 00:16:36,853
Darryl, the airport
wants to buy your place.

285
00:16:36,919 --> 00:16:40,825
Airports come under federal law.
Federal? I just do small stuff.

286
00:16:40,898 --> 00:16:42,758
Conveyancing, magistrates.

287
00:16:42,824 --> 00:16:45,549
- You defended Wayne.
- Yeah, and he got eight years.

288
00:16:45,616 --> 00:16:48,942
Yeah, but you did your best.
I mean, you can hold your head up high.

289
00:16:49,018 --> 00:16:51,196
He was the one that
held up the service station.

290
00:16:51,265 --> 00:16:54,242
- I don't know anything
about this sort of stuff.
- But they can't do this.

291
00:16:54,315 --> 00:16:57,553
- I don't know. Maybe they can.
- They can't.

292
00:16:57,620 --> 00:17:00,563
Look, I'll ring around
and I'll see what I can find out.

293
00:17:00,636 --> 00:17:03,197
Good on you, Dennis. Eh.

294
00:17:03,269 --> 00:17:05,128
How is Wayne?

295
00:17:05,194 --> 00:17:08,914
Good. Yeah, good.
Behaving himself.

296
00:17:08,980 --> 00:17:11,192
- Any word?
- Nah, nah.

297
00:17:11,260 --> 00:17:14,652
They reckon he's still
a couple of years off.

298
00:17:14,725 --> 00:17:16,837
I'll let you know.

299
00:17:16,908 --> 00:17:19,305
<i>But Dad was never one
to bring worries home.</i>

300
00:17:20,343 --> 00:17:24,512
<i>Even in the down times he'd still
tell us funny stories about his day.</i>

301
00:17:24,579 --> 00:17:28,387
It's a head-on between
a Geo and a Volksy.

302
00:17:28,462 --> 00:17:32,368
Dad also had a way
of making everyone feel important.

303
00:17:32,441 --> 00:17:35,232
Come on, Dale.
Tell 'em.

304
00:17:35,298 --> 00:17:38,887
Go on. Tell 'em.
Dale dug a hole.

305
00:17:38,958 --> 00:17:41,649
- Like the time I dug a hole.
- Started the patio.

306
00:17:41,717 --> 00:17:45,372
- Good on you, Dale.
- And he'd compliment Mum every
single night on her cooking.

307
00:17:45,440 --> 00:17:49,161
Well, hello.
How's this, boys? Whoo-hoo!

308
00:17:49,227 --> 00:17:51,624
- What do you call this?
- Chicken.

309
00:17:51,698 --> 00:17:54,839
- Yeah, but it's got something
sprinkled on it.
- Seasoning.

310
00:17:54,909 --> 00:17:56,769
Seasoning.

311
00:17:56,834 --> 00:17:59,558
Looks like everybody's
kicked a goal.

312
00:17:59,626 --> 00:18:01,486
How are our
backs feeling?

313
00:18:01,551 --> 00:18:04,595
<i>Steve did get them
ergonometric chairs.</i>

314
00:18:04,664 --> 00:18:07,355
<i>And Mum had already
started prettying hers up.</i>

315
00:18:07,425 --> 00:18:10,499
<i>Dad placed a great deal
of importance on mealtime.</i>

316
00:18:10,570 --> 00:18:12,430
<i>He had
a very strict rule:</i>

317
00:18:12,495 --> 00:18:16,786
<i>When the family starts to eat,
the television is definitely
turned down.</i>

318
00:18:16,861 --> 00:18:21,095
<i>But as soon as we've finished eating,
it's a different story.</i>

319
00:18:21,160 --> 00:18:23,820
That was great.

320
00:18:23,889 --> 00:18:26,745
Dad, 7:30.

321
00:18:26,809 --> 00:18:29,917
All right,
time for some fun.

322
00:18:29,987 --> 00:18:33,708
<i>Dad reckons there's only one show better
than Funniest Home Videos,</i>

323
00:18:33,774 --> 00:18:36,532
<i>and that's The Best
of Funniest Home Videos.</i>

324
00:18:36,598 --> 00:18:40,253
<i>It made Dad laugh. And when Dad laughed,
his whole body joined in.</i>

325
00:18:40,322 --> 00:18:42,270
<i>And then we would too.</i>

326
00:18:42,343 --> 00:18:44,520
Doggy breath!

327
00:18:44,588 --> 00:18:49,076
<i>It was funny how on the fun nights,
part of me got sad,</i>

328
00:18:49,146 --> 00:18:52,352
<i>'cause I'd think about
my big brother in prison
and wonder what he was doing.</i>

329
00:18:53,864 --> 00:18:56,260
<i>Wayne always reckoned
he was doing fine,</i>

330
00:18:56,337 --> 00:19:00,539
<i>but I get the feeling
he was missing us more
than he was letting on.</i>

331
00:19:00,604 --> 00:19:03,165
<i>It'll be great
when he comes home.</i>

332
00:19:10,617 --> 00:19:12,730
You're a ripper, Dennis.

333
00:19:12,801 --> 00:19:17,035
I said you're
a bloody ripper!

334
00:19:17,100 --> 00:19:20,493
Yeah, okay.

335
00:19:20,567 --> 00:19:24,604
- That's it, Sal. All fixed.
- What did he say?

336
00:19:24,674 --> 00:19:29,357
He said I have recourse
to the Administrative Appeals Tribunal.

337
00:19:29,426 --> 00:19:32,751
All I gotta do is run
up there, put my case,
and they can go and get stuffed.

338
00:19:32,828 --> 00:19:34,688
Good on you, darl.

339
00:19:34,753 --> 00:19:37,511
- He still hasn't noticed, Mum.
- What?

340
00:19:37,577 --> 00:19:41,297
- Oh, it's finished.
- Today.

341
00:19:41,365 --> 00:19:44,373
How is that?
You should open a shop.

342
00:19:44,444 --> 00:19:48,133
Dad, some guy's selling
an overhead projector.

343
00:19:48,201 --> 00:19:50,061
Nah--

344
00:19:50,126 --> 00:19:52,949
Nah, hang on, Steve.
What's he asking?

345
00:19:53,014 --> 00:19:56,319
- One-fifty.
- Tell him he's dreaming.

346
00:19:56,384 --> 00:19:59,623
- Yeah.
- So what else
did Dennis have to say?

347
00:19:59,689 --> 00:20:02,599
- Nothing. It's fixed.
- Yeah, but when's the hearing?

348
00:20:02,675 --> 00:20:05,171
Monday. And I know exactly
what I'm gonna say.

349
00:20:05,242 --> 00:20:08,700
- Don't babble on, darl.
- I don't babble on.
When do I babble on?

350
00:20:08,773 --> 00:20:11,497
- You do babble on.
- All right.

351
00:20:11,565 --> 00:20:14,387
But I tell you
what we're gonna do.

352
00:20:14,453 --> 00:20:17,080
Friday we're gonna
pick up Trace and Con,

353
00:20:17,149 --> 00:20:21,154
and then we're going straight up
to Bonnie Doon for the weekend.

354
00:20:21,225 --> 00:20:25,394
And we're not worrying about
those clowns for another second.

355
00:20:25,462 --> 00:20:29,248
- Mum! Price is Right'son.
- All right, eh.

356
00:20:29,313 --> 00:20:33,099
I'd better ring up Farouk and Jack
and Evonne and the others...

357
00:20:33,165 --> 00:20:36,207
and tell 'em
what's going on.

358
00:20:41,830 --> 00:20:45,999
<i>Trace and Con had
a great honeymoon in Thailand.</i>

359
00:20:46,066 --> 00:20:48,889
<i>We met them as they came off
the plane with a baggage cart,</i>

360
00:20:48,954 --> 00:20:51,777
<i>which was lucky 'cause
they had heaps of stuff.</i>

361
00:20:53,768 --> 00:20:56,974
<i>We couldn't wait to hear all
the stories about their trip,</i>

362
00:20:57,042 --> 00:20:59,384
<i>and we didn't have
to wait all that long either.</i>

363
00:20:59,450 --> 00:21:02,174
<i>'Cause one of the good things
about living next to the airport...</i>

364
00:21:02,241 --> 00:21:04,582
<i>is that it doesn't
take long to walk home.</i>

365
00:21:14,823 --> 00:21:17,996
And they had these masks
which you put over your eyes
when you're sleeping...

366
00:21:18,064 --> 00:21:19,924
so that you can't
see anything.

367
00:21:19,989 --> 00:21:22,330
- And they were complimentary.
- Yeah, they were for free.

368
00:21:22,397 --> 00:21:24,376
<i>It was the first time
anyone in our family...</i>

369
00:21:24,451 --> 00:21:26,311
<i>had traveled
outside the county.</i>

370
00:21:26,377 --> 00:21:28,554
<i>And we just sat glued
listening to all the details.</i>

371
00:21:28,623 --> 00:21:31,248
Oh, Mum, we had a choice between fish
and Beef Wellington.

372
00:21:31,318 --> 00:21:34,010
- Beef Wellington?
- What's that, darl?

373
00:21:34,080 --> 00:21:36,289
It's beef
done in pastry.

374
00:21:36,357 --> 00:21:38,885
And it was an absolute
credit to the airline.

375
00:21:38,957 --> 00:21:40,818
- Did they show a film?
- Two.

376
00:21:40,884 --> 00:21:42,744
- Two?
- Yeah.

377
00:21:42,809 --> 00:21:44,855
- And they also had--
- What were they?

378
00:21:44,927 --> 00:21:47,936
- We saw Twister. And they had--
- Was it on a screen or a telly?

379
00:21:48,007 --> 00:21:51,913
Telly. And they had
easy listening, classic gold,
contemporary rock, world--

380
00:21:51,987 --> 00:21:54,165
What was the other one,
the other film?

381
00:21:54,234 --> 00:21:56,575
- Uh,Juman-- Jumanji, yeah.
-Jumanji.

382
00:21:56,791 --> 00:21:59,559
- And with the headphones--
- Which one was first?

383
00:21:59,624 --> 00:22:01,946
- Twister. You could
turn the sound all--
- How many on the way back?

384
00:22:02,012 --> 00:22:04,813
- Dale! You can ask all this later.
- Sorry, Trace.

385
00:22:04,878 --> 00:22:07,895
It was so dry in the plane
that your hair actually dehydrates.

386
00:22:07,966 --> 00:22:11,839
- Doesn't it, Con?
- It loses its moisture.
- It's so interesting.

387
00:22:11,914 --> 00:22:13,489
<i>We could have
listened for hours,</i>

388
00:22:14,067 --> 00:22:15,728
<i>but then it
was presents time.</i>

389
00:22:16,001 --> 00:22:18,889
For you, Dad. It's a samurai sword
letter opener.

390
00:22:18,963 --> 00:22:20,992
That is handcrafted.

391
00:22:21,064 --> 00:22:24,592
How's that, love?
That is just--

392
00:22:24,660 --> 00:22:27,038
This is going straight
to the poolroom.

393
00:22:27,112 --> 00:22:29,305
You should use it, Dad.

394
00:22:29,374 --> 00:22:32,325
This I am not even taking
out of the wrapper.

395
00:22:32,398 --> 00:22:36,847
<i>They bought Mum a genuine Rolex
for 15 bucks off a guy at the beach.</i>

396
00:22:36,919 --> 00:22:39,047
<i>He said he'd mail
the warranty later.</i>

397
00:22:39,115 --> 00:22:43,218
<i>I got a necklace with a shark tooth.
They got a Walkman for Steve.</i>

398
00:22:43,286 --> 00:22:46,565
<i>'Cause it was Friday,
I told Trace I'd take
Wayne's present to him.</i>

399
00:22:46,629 --> 00:22:49,580
<i>It was an elephant,
'cause elephants bring good luck,</i>

400
00:22:49,653 --> 00:22:52,257
<i>especially if the trunks are up,
and his trunk was up.</i>

401
00:22:53,283 --> 00:22:56,018
<i>It really made Wayne's day.</i>

402
00:22:56,084 --> 00:22:58,819
- She's great, isn't she? Trace.
- Yeah.

403
00:22:58,885 --> 00:23:02,184
It brings good luck.
She's coming in on Monday.

404
00:23:02,260 --> 00:23:04,833
Great. And when's Dad going in
to do that hearing?

405
00:23:04,903 --> 00:23:06,749
- On Monday.
- Yeah?

406
00:23:06,813 --> 00:23:11,198
- Yeah. He reckons they can't do it.
- Dad would know.

407
00:23:11,271 --> 00:23:15,340
- You going up to
Bonnie Doon tonight?
- Yeah. Maybe. I don't know.

408
00:23:15,409 --> 00:23:18,589
<i>I didn't want to tell Wayne
that we were going to Bonnie Doon,</i>

409
00:23:18,655 --> 00:23:21,456
<i>just in case he'd feel bad
that we were going to Bonnie Doon.</i>

410
00:23:21,521 --> 00:23:25,069
<i>He liked it there.
We all liked it there.</i>

411
00:23:25,204 --> 00:23:28,013
* We're going to Bonnie Doon *

412
00:23:28,079 --> 00:23:30,967
<i>We all left soon after,
except for Trace and Con.</i>

413
00:23:31,041 --> 00:23:34,502
<i>As you can just imagine,
they were just married and
wanted some time to themselves.</i>

414
00:23:34,574 --> 00:23:36,734
<i>So they drove up
in their own car.</i>

415
00:23:36,803 --> 00:23:39,537
<i>Dad had a song he used to sing
about going to Bonnie Doon.</i>

416
00:23:39,604 --> 00:23:42,556
<i>Only he sang it a lot,
and it was a bit repetitive.</i>

417
00:23:42,628 --> 00:23:44,473
Darl!

418
00:23:50,184 --> 00:23:52,821
- Dad, radar!

419
00:23:59,873 --> 00:24:02,205
- How much did that cost?
- Seventy bucks.

420
00:24:02,337 --> 00:24:04,651
Just paid for itself.

421
00:24:06,529 --> 00:24:09,069
Dale, why don't you
unload the boat, Mate?

422
00:24:09,221 --> 00:24:12,139
Steve, don't forget
the dog food, pal.

423
00:24:16,566 --> 00:24:19,963
Hey, boy. Hey!

424
00:24:20,036 --> 00:24:24,552
- Bloody marvelous to be
up here, isn't it, Dale?
- Yeah.

425
00:24:24,619 --> 00:24:27,583
- Bonnie Doon.
- Dad loved Bonnie Doon.

426
00:24:27,600 --> 00:24:28,852
<i>How do I describe it?</i>

427
00:24:29,063 --> 00:24:31,256
<i>It is a little town
on a big lake.</i>

428
00:24:31,324 --> 00:24:35,840
<i>It's a beautiful place,
especially this time of year
when the water levels are down.</i>

429
00:24:35,909 --> 00:24:38,481
<i>Dad could not believe his luck
when he found this place.</i>

430
00:24:38,551 --> 00:24:40,875
<i>It was a bargain,
and he couldn't work out why.</i>

431
00:24:40,939 --> 00:24:43,826
<i>It was just a block of land
with a beautiful view.</i>

432
00:24:43,900 --> 00:24:46,570
<i>It took him five years
to build this place.</i>

433
00:24:46,638 --> 00:24:49,210
<i>He bought an unfinished kit home
out of the Trading Post,</i>

434
00:24:49,280 --> 00:24:52,579
<i>built it in the backyard
and towed it up here with his truck.</i>

435
00:24:52,655 --> 00:24:54,977
<i>He was the only bloke
he knew with a holiday home.</i>

436
00:24:55,043 --> 00:24:57,105
<i>Not a mobile home,
a holiday home.</i>

437
00:24:57,175 --> 00:24:59,650
<i>And he reckoned we were
the luckiest family in the world.</i>

438
00:24:59,722 --> 00:25:04,248
- Dale, I reckon we're the luckiest
family in the world. - Yeah.

439
00:25:04,249 --> 00:25:05,291
<i>He loved the serenity of the place.</i>

440
00:25:05,357 --> 00:25:07,296
How's the serenity?

441
00:25:07,435 --> 00:25:09,544
<i>I think he also just loved the word.</i>

442
00:25:09,673 --> 00:25:11,797
So much serenity.

443
00:25:13,300 --> 00:25:17,199
Let's get to bed.
Tomorrow is going to be a great day.

444
00:25:17,200 --> 00:25:17,931
Yeah.

445
00:25:21,166 --> 00:25:23,609
<i>If there's one thing
Dad loved more than serenity,</i>

446
00:25:23,680 --> 00:25:26,156
<i>it was an outboard motor
on full throttle.</i>

447
00:25:32,944 --> 00:25:36,343
Listen to that!
Singing like a bird!

448
00:25:36,414 --> 00:25:39,684
<i>He just loved Bonnie Doon,
and he reckoned the faster you went,</i>

449
00:25:39,684 --> 00:25:40,918
<i>the more you saw of it.</i>

450
00:25:40,975 --> 00:25:41,919
Look at that!

451
00:25:42,487 --> 00:25:45,538
- What?
- Back there.

452
00:25:45,539 --> 00:25:49,616
<i>But eventually he found a place
he reckoned looked like a good spot.</i>

453
00:25:49,617 --> 00:25:52,006
I reckon this looks like a good spot.

454
00:25:53,069 --> 00:25:56,047
<i>Dad loved fishing. And he really
looked after his equipment.</i>

455
00:25:56,460 --> 00:26:00,021
<i>He said they only made on good rod,
it's called the 'ugly stick'.</i>

456
00:26:00,166 --> 00:26:04,285
<i>It's so strong, you can bend it
right around on itself.</i>

457
00:26:04,286 --> 00:26:07,584
Look at that.
Bends right around itself.

458
00:26:08,988 --> 00:26:11,636
<i>The lake had trout,
redfin and carp.</i>

459
00:26:11,707 --> 00:26:14,575
<i>The carp was not a good eating fish,
but it was good catching.</i>

460
00:26:14,575 --> 00:26:16,484
<i>They could grow
to quite a size.</i>

461
00:26:16,485 --> 00:26:19,860
<i>Genuinely, that just hooked himself.
But occasionally Dad went crafty.</i>

462
00:26:21,462 --> 00:26:22,662
- Got a nibble.

463
00:26:23,032 --> 00:26:27,100
<i>Dad reckoned that fishing
was 10 percent brains
and 95 percent muscle...</i>

464
00:26:27,100 --> 00:26:29,340
<i>and the rest
was just good luck.</i>

465
00:26:31,733 --> 00:26:35,996
<i>We pulled off a few carp that day.
And each of us had a muscle ache.</i>

466
00:26:40,295 --> 00:26:42,496
- Where's Con?
- Down the shops.

467
00:26:42,996 --> 00:26:44,609
You and Con talked about kids, yet?

468
00:26:45,311 --> 00:26:47,531
Yeah, Con wants to start
straight away.

469
00:26:47,532 --> 00:26:49,153
But, you know,
I've got a career.

470
00:26:49,154 --> 00:26:50,343
Of course.

471
00:26:50,344 --> 00:26:53,005
So, I said I'm not having kids
until I'm at least 23.

472
00:26:53,006 --> 00:26:54,868
Times have changed.

473
00:27:09,100 --> 00:27:11,235
- Gale had a boy.
- Was he a whopper?

474
00:27:11,236 --> 00:27:14,233
10 pounds. They got to be
a big beefy family.

475
00:27:14,234 --> 00:27:18,472
Tyler Jake. Even the birth notice
was beef. Stork and everything.

476
00:27:18,473 --> 00:27:20,891
Shannon was 9 pounds.
Would you mind then?

477
00:27:20,892 --> 00:27:23,720
Uh, I needed a pair of booties.
You always liked booties.

478
00:27:24,306 --> 00:27:26,891
- I reckon you should make
faked flowers. - Uh, yeah.

479
00:27:27,145 --> 00:27:28,939
- Jenny makes fake flowers.
- Jenny?

480
00:27:28,940 --> 00:27:30,159
- Yeah.
- Jenny Jenny?

481
00:27:30,160 --> 00:27:32,317
No, Malcoway Jenny. She reckons
the trick is to make 'em real

482
00:27:32,318 --> 00:27:35,208
but not too real. Just real enough
to know that they're fake.

483
00:27:36,082 --> 00:27:38,856
- I'd like to do pottery.
- Wow, on a wheel?

484
00:27:38,860 --> 00:27:41,363
Yeah. I just love mugs.

485
00:27:42,100 --> 00:27:43,946
Yeah, I'd like
to make my own mugs.

486
00:27:45,100 --> 00:27:46,676
- Mum?
- Yeah?

487
00:27:46,925 --> 00:27:48,237
- What's the matter?
- Nothing.

488
00:27:49,272 --> 00:27:50,432
- You worried about the house?
- No.

489
00:27:50,499 --> 00:27:55,099
- Well, Dad said everything's
going to be okay.
- Of course it is, darl.

490
00:28:00,584 --> 00:28:03,680
We ended up
with four carp and one redfin.

491
00:28:03,749 --> 00:28:08,185
A reasonable day's fishing,
considering we had to get back
earlier when Coco got seasick.

492
00:28:08,258 --> 00:28:10,808
Steve wasn't looking
all that good either.

493
00:28:15,707 --> 00:28:18,519
Keep it still, Trace.

494
00:28:20,310 --> 00:28:22,163
Disciplined,
isn't he, Sal?

495
00:28:24,339 --> 00:28:28,111
Here are you and I relaxing,
having a beer, and he's still training.

496
00:28:28,176 --> 00:28:30,563
Yeah, he just loves
that sport.

497
00:28:30,637 --> 00:28:34,147
- Well, you gotta have
a passion for something.
- Yeah.

498
00:28:36,966 --> 00:28:40,063
Ours is serenity.

499
00:28:42,466 --> 00:28:45,812
Dad, where do you want me to put
the chicken coop?

500
00:28:45,887 --> 00:28:48,307
Out the back, Steve.

501
00:28:50,684 --> 00:28:54,128
Forty-five bucks. You couldn't buy
the materials for that.

502
00:28:54,199 --> 00:28:57,066
Now, what do you want
with a chicken coop?

503
00:28:57,142 --> 00:28:59,473
And what do we want
with a kit home?

504
00:28:59,538 --> 00:29:02,983
Oh, yeah, yeah,
yeah, yeah.

505
00:29:03,056 --> 00:29:06,282
Now, give me a kiss,
you big hunk of a man.

506
00:29:40,042 --> 00:29:44,006
Marvellous, ain't it?
The lake, the kids.

507
00:29:48,037 --> 00:29:51,327
Oh, look at the dogs.
Don't they love it?

508
00:29:54,276 --> 00:29:56,156
Oh, smell that.

509
00:29:57,340 --> 00:29:59,512
- Diesel.
- Yep.

510
00:30:01,712 --> 00:30:03,980
Pity Wayne can't be here.

511
00:30:04,046 --> 00:30:07,490
- Darl.
- No, no, I could've done better.

512
00:30:09,001 --> 00:30:12,478
Well, let's start
cooking this feast.

513
00:30:12,550 --> 00:30:15,416
- Who ordered medium rare?
- Me.

514
00:30:15,492 --> 00:30:17,345
Good stuff.

515
00:30:17,410 --> 00:30:20,025
Check that, Steve.
It could be a little underdone.

516
00:30:20,094 --> 00:30:24,434
- I bet they don't have places
like this in Thailand, Con.
- No, Mr. Kerrigan.

517
00:30:24,507 --> 00:30:27,352
Hey, hey, hey.
"Darryl" now, mate.

518
00:30:27,416 --> 00:30:29,618
Sorry, Darryl.

519
00:30:29,686 --> 00:30:33,392
- It's a good place, though.
- Yeah, yeah, I'm curious.

520
00:30:33,460 --> 00:30:37,710
Now, I know it's unfair
to compare anyplace to Bonnie Doon,

521
00:30:37,775 --> 00:30:40,107
but why would I want to go there
instead of here?

522
00:30:40,173 --> 00:30:42,985
- It's for young people, Dad.
- I know that, Trace.

523
00:30:43,050 --> 00:30:46,560
- It's the culture, Darryl.
The place is full of culture.
- Chockers.

524
00:30:46,631 --> 00:30:48,484
- Oh, yeah.
- Something for everyone.

525
00:30:48,550 --> 00:30:50,719
- What was that movie again, Con?
- Dale.

526
00:30:50,787 --> 00:30:52,640
There were so many stories.

527
00:30:52,705 --> 00:30:55,038
At the hotel
Trace and I were staying in,
they had this one channel:

528
00:30:55,103 --> 00:30:57,523
kickboxing, 24 hours a day.

529
00:30:58,393 --> 00:31:01,485
It was just so interesting
to hear about another county.

530
00:31:01,486 --> 00:31:04,647
Meals were 5 dollars, mum.
The most beautiful sadeys(?).

531
00:31:04,648 --> 00:31:05,445
What's that, darl?

532
00:31:05,446 --> 00:31:08,786
It's meat on skew with
peanut sauce and wheat.

533
00:31:08,798 --> 00:31:11,381
And the stories
went on and on all night.

534
00:31:11,531 --> 00:31:14,756
The value for money is
absolutely second to none.

535
00:31:14,757 --> 00:31:17,296
- One of the other Sony Walkmans.
- With presets?

536
00:31:17,297 --> 00:31:21,466
Yeah, presets and megabytes.
$85 dollars Australian.

537
00:31:21,797 --> 00:31:23,495
- Wow.
- Bargain?

538
00:31:24,888 --> 00:31:27,674
But I reckon someone like you, Steve,
could have got it down even further.

539
00:31:28,721 --> 00:31:30,596
I can't wait to get a beer and coffee.

540
00:31:31,250 --> 00:31:34,251
- It's great to have you two back.
- It's great to be back.

541
00:31:34,742 --> 00:31:37,130
Great to be up here.

542
00:31:37,204 --> 00:31:40,911
They haven't got
a place like this in Bangkok.

543
00:31:40,977 --> 00:31:43,276
How's the serenity?

544
00:31:44,878 --> 00:31:46,731
Not a sound.

545
00:31:58,881 --> 00:32:01,944
- Feeling good, Sal.
- Good on you, darl.

546
00:32:02,014 --> 00:32:04,183
Steve, could you move
the Corolla?

547
00:32:04,252 --> 00:32:06,584
I need to get to the Torana out
so I can get to the Commodore.

548
00:32:06,650 --> 00:32:08,982
I'll have to get the keys
to the Cortina if I'm going
to move that Corolla.

549
00:32:09,047 --> 00:32:11,379
- Watch the boat, mate.
- Yeah.

550
00:32:11,446 --> 00:32:13,865
- Know why I'm feeling good, Sal?
- Why?

551
00:32:13,939 --> 00:32:17,710
I'll tell you why.
Because this is an example
of the individual.

552
00:32:17,775 --> 00:32:20,424
Of how the individual,
if he has the guts to stand up...

553
00:32:20,494 --> 00:32:23,687
and shove it right up
those people who think
they can stand on top of you.

554
00:32:23,754 --> 00:32:26,980
The people who think
they can do that, that's why.

555
00:32:32,163 --> 00:32:34,103
What do you mean
what's my plea?

556
00:32:34,353 --> 00:32:36,587
- What is the case you are putting?
- I told you.

557
00:32:36,655 --> 00:32:39,685
I mean, you just can't walk in
and take a man's house.

558
00:32:39,756 --> 00:32:42,568
Mr. Kerrigan, are you disputing
the amount of compensation?

559
00:32:42,633 --> 00:32:47,298
I'm not interested in compensation.
I'm saying that you can't kick me out.

560
00:32:47,364 --> 00:32:49,566
Very well.

561
00:32:49,635 --> 00:32:51,999
- What is your argument?
- That's it.

562
00:32:52,064 --> 00:32:55,739
That's my argument.
You can't kick me out.

563
00:32:55,805 --> 00:32:59,631
And on what law do you base
that argument?

564
00:32:59,706 --> 00:33:03,118
- The law
of bloody common sense!
- Mr. Kerrigan.

565
00:33:03,190 --> 00:33:06,635
- I must ask you
to restrain yourself.
- Yeah, all right.

566
00:33:06,707 --> 00:33:10,959
Mr. Kerrigan, this is
the Administrative Appeals Tribunal.

567
00:33:11,024 --> 00:33:14,217
You are an applicant.
You need to show--

568
00:33:14,284 --> 00:33:17,859
I need to show?
So it's up to me, is it?

569
00:33:17,929 --> 00:33:21,439
Mr. Kerrigan, Air Link,
as a federal authority,

570
00:33:21,510 --> 00:33:24,093
has the right to purchase property
compulsorily.

571
00:33:24,164 --> 00:33:28,763
And, as far as I can see,
you have offered no evidence
to refute that right.

572
00:33:28,832 --> 00:33:30,772
No evidence?

573
00:33:30,845 --> 00:33:35,315
It's not a house. It's a home.
A man's home is his castle.

574
00:33:35,385 --> 00:33:40,138
I mean, it's-- it's--
it's Jack's castle.
It's Farou-Farouk's castle.

575
00:33:40,212 --> 00:33:42,480
You just can't walk in
and steal our homes.

576
00:33:42,547 --> 00:33:45,359
- You will be compensated.
- I don't wanna be compensated.

577
00:33:45,424 --> 00:33:47,756
You can't buy
what I've got.

578
00:33:49,260 --> 00:33:52,553
Mr. Kerrigan, I am rapidly
running out of patience.

579
00:33:52,618 --> 00:33:56,128
- You're running out of patience.
- What is your case in law?

580
00:33:58,117 --> 00:34:00,449
Well, okay, um,

581
00:34:00,514 --> 00:34:05,430
the law is supposed
to be about justice-- no, fairness.

582
00:34:05,502 --> 00:34:10,450
And I know that sometimes
what is right and fair is
not clear-cut. It's a bit iffy.

583
00:34:10,522 --> 00:34:15,372
But this is not iffy.
I mean, this is as clear as day.

584
00:34:15,444 --> 00:34:20,393
It is right and fair
that a family be allowed
to live in its own house.

585
00:34:20,464 --> 00:34:22,764
That is justice.

586
00:34:24,269 --> 00:34:26,755
I rest my case.

587
00:34:28,872 --> 00:34:32,513
<i>Dad reckoned he'd nailed it.
Farouk agreed.</i>

588
00:34:35,202 --> 00:34:37,753
<i>But Dad was wrong.</i>

589
00:34:37,825 --> 00:34:42,610
I can't believe I lost.
I've let you down.

590
00:34:42,684 --> 00:34:45,976
No, no, Mr. Kerrigan.
You do good job.

591
00:34:46,040 --> 00:34:49,104
- Please, Farouk, call me Darryl.
- Okay, Mr. Darryl.

592
00:34:49,174 --> 00:34:52,170
But, you know, I never heard that one
you say before.

593
00:34:52,243 --> 00:34:55,403
"A man's home is his castle."
Well, that's an old saying.

594
00:34:55,472 --> 00:34:59,658
No, no. Other one. Other one.
"Is not house, is home."

595
00:34:59,724 --> 00:35:02,657
Farouk, I lost.

596
00:35:02,730 --> 00:35:05,248
I know, Mr. Darryl.

597
00:35:05,319 --> 00:35:07,837
Farouk, how much
are they paying you?

598
00:35:07,909 --> 00:35:10,972
- $65,000.
- For your place?

599
00:35:11,042 --> 00:35:15,261
Yes. They say the plane,
they fly overhead, drop the value.

600
00:35:15,326 --> 00:35:19,152
I don't care. In Beirut,
plane fly overhead, drop bomb.

601
00:35:19,227 --> 00:35:23,282
- I like this plane.
- What are we going to do, Darryl?

602
00:35:23,351 --> 00:35:25,236
I don't know, Jack.

603
00:35:25,302 --> 00:35:29,008
This is the only place I can afford.
I don't wanna move.

604
00:35:29,074 --> 00:35:30,927
You see what
they're doing, Sal?

605
00:35:30,992 --> 00:35:33,063
Mm.

606
00:35:33,133 --> 00:35:36,643
- How long you lived here, Jack?
- Three years.

607
00:35:36,714 --> 00:35:40,126
Now, in the area.
How long have you lived around here?

608
00:35:40,199 --> 00:35:42,205
Fifty-seven years.

609
00:35:42,278 --> 00:35:45,657
Fifty-seven years.

610
00:35:45,730 --> 00:35:49,786
And they're gonna
kick you out on your ass.

611
00:35:49,855 --> 00:35:54,041
Well, bugger 'em.
I'm not giving up, Jack.

612
00:35:54,107 --> 00:35:58,359
If they wanna play things by the law,
fine. We'll play by the law.

613
00:35:58,423 --> 00:36:01,268
But they're not
the only big guns in town.

614
00:36:01,333 --> 00:36:05,606
If it's gonna be lawyers, I'm gonna
hit them with the big artillery.

615
00:36:05,712 --> 00:36:09,986
Hang on, Darryl.
Jesus, these fucking photocopiers.

616
00:36:10,060 --> 00:36:12,873
What the fuck is that?
I cleared tray three.

617
00:36:12,938 --> 00:36:14,791
Why don't you get your girl
to do that for you?

618
00:36:14,856 --> 00:36:18,845
She's not here on Mondays.
She does Tuesday, Thursday, Friday.

619
00:36:18,916 --> 00:36:21,564
F-3. What the fuck
is that?

620
00:36:21,634 --> 00:36:23,771
- Dennis, how did it go?
- Not good.

621
00:36:23,839 --> 00:36:27,611
I spoke to every barrister I know.
No one wants to touch it.

622
00:36:27,676 --> 00:36:29,911
All right. You do it.

623
00:36:29,977 --> 00:36:32,365
I told you, Darryl,
I'm not qualified.

624
00:36:32,440 --> 00:36:35,699
You're not qualified?
Now I've heard everything.

625
00:36:35,766 --> 00:36:37,835
What do you mean
you're not qualified?

626
00:36:37,907 --> 00:36:40,174
I mean I'm not
in the big time.

627
00:36:40,241 --> 00:36:42,148
You have lost faith
in yourself, Dennis.

628
00:36:42,224 --> 00:36:44,904
- Darryl--
- You have lost faith.

629
00:36:44,972 --> 00:36:48,766
Darryl, it's over my head.
It's over your head too.

630
00:36:48,841 --> 00:36:52,612
Over my head? Dennis.

631
00:36:52,678 --> 00:36:55,675
- Darryl, have you heard
of the Barlow Group?
-No.

632
00:36:55,747 --> 00:36:59,127
It's basically a big investment company
controlled by three blokes...

633
00:36:59,199 --> 00:37:01,052
worth about
a half a billion each.

634
00:37:01,117 --> 00:37:03,570
Well, the Barlow Group
is Air Link.

635
00:37:03,643 --> 00:37:05,780
I thought Air Link
was the government.

636
00:37:05,850 --> 00:37:09,807
It's a government authority,
but all the money's coming from Barlow.

637
00:37:09,877 --> 00:37:14,282
It's a way of privatizing
without privatizing.
Anyway, it's a big, big thing.

638
00:37:14,354 --> 00:37:17,220
Every level of government.
Huge investment.

639
00:37:18,254 --> 00:37:20,292
All right, fine.
So they're big.

640
00:37:20,364 --> 00:37:22,272
But why do they
wantmy house?

641
00:37:22,346 --> 00:37:25,605
Why don't they just fill in
the old quarry and build it there?

642
00:37:25,671 --> 00:37:28,570
I don't know. Maybe it's just cheaper
to pull down more houses.

643
00:37:28,645 --> 00:37:33,147
- So we fight 'em.
- Darryl, they want this thing to work.

644
00:37:33,217 --> 00:37:37,970
- They're gonna get their way.
- And you know why people
like that get their way?

645
00:37:38,044 --> 00:37:41,337
Because people like us
don't stand up to 'em.

646
00:37:41,401 --> 00:37:43,504
Now, they've still
gotta play by the rules.

647
00:37:43,575 --> 00:37:47,401
Darryl, they write the rules.
They own the game.

648
00:37:47,475 --> 00:37:51,246
Fuck, Dennis. It's my fucking house.
You're not gonna run scared on me.

649
00:37:52,622 --> 00:37:54,858
I can't do this by myself.

650
00:37:54,925 --> 00:37:57,606
All right, mate.

651
00:37:57,674 --> 00:38:00,290
Let me think about it.

652
00:38:04,835 --> 00:38:08,891
- Con's working late tonight.
- He's just so busy.

653
00:38:08,961 --> 00:38:11,773
I cannot believe
this postcard arrived today.

654
00:38:11,838 --> 00:38:13,843
Thanks
for dropping in.

655
00:38:13,916 --> 00:38:15,920
How's he treating
my princess?

656
00:38:15,993 --> 00:38:17,846
Dad!

657
00:38:17,912 --> 00:38:20,626
All right,
all right.

658
00:38:20,693 --> 00:38:23,560
You saw
some amazing things.

659
00:38:23,635 --> 00:38:26,186
Now, that is
a bloody big statue.

660
00:38:26,256 --> 00:38:29,385
- Yeah, and it's all made of gold.
