00:52:58,599 --> 00:53:00,452
Oh, yeah,
sure, sure.

885
00:53:00,518 --> 00:53:03,613
I was just starting general,
and then I was getting...
more specific...

886
00:53:03,682 --> 00:53:07,541
with the-- the, um--
Just one moment, please.

887
00:53:07,615 --> 00:53:09,784
The, um--

888
00:53:09,854 --> 00:53:13,112
Jesus, Darryl,
I am sweatin' here.

889
00:53:13,178 --> 00:53:15,217
You're killin' them,
Dennis.

890
00:53:15,288 --> 00:53:17,674
I don't even know
Roman numerals.

891
00:53:17,750 --> 00:53:20,878
Um-- It's-- It's--

892
00:53:20,946 --> 00:53:22,800
Ju--
I've got it here.

893
00:53:22,865 --> 00:53:26,691
It's the... section 51,

894
00:53:26,766 --> 00:53:30,058
uh, second
from the bottom.

895
00:53:31,369 --> 00:53:33,887
"The Parliament shall
have power to make laws...

896
00:53:33,959 --> 00:53:37,054
with respect to copyrights,
patents of inventions...

897
00:53:37,123 --> 00:53:39,293
and designs
and trademarks."

898
00:53:39,362 --> 00:53:41,880
It's all part of it.

899
00:53:41,952 --> 00:53:44,251
This is what I'm getting at.
That's my point.

900
00:53:44,317 --> 00:53:46,486
It's-- It's
the vibe of it.

901
00:53:46,556 --> 00:53:49,521
All right. Taken.

902
00:53:49,592 --> 00:53:52,078
Do you have a precedent
which supports...

903
00:53:52,150 --> 00:53:54,352
this...vibe?

904
00:53:54,421 --> 00:53:57,451
Uh... yes.

905
00:53:57,521 --> 00:54:00,552
Yes, I do.
Um, just one moment.

906
00:54:02,030 --> 00:54:05,125
What's the name
of the famous aboriginal?

907
00:54:05,195 --> 00:54:07,364
- Cathy Freeman.
- No, the court case.

908
00:54:07,433 --> 00:54:09,983
- Evonne Goolagong.
- No, no, no. Ma-- Mabo.

909
00:54:10,054 --> 00:54:11,961
Mabo.

910
00:54:12,037 --> 00:54:14,522
What about it?

911
00:54:14,594 --> 00:54:18,136
That's your classic case
of big business...

912
00:54:18,207 --> 00:54:20,093
trying to take land,

913
00:54:20,157 --> 00:54:22,010
and they couldn't.

914
00:54:22,075 --> 00:54:24,942
Mr. Denuto,
the Mabo decision...

915
00:54:25,017 --> 00:54:29,388
pertains to the specific
issue of native land title
and terra nullius.

916
00:54:29,461 --> 00:54:31,346
Yeah.

917
00:54:31,410 --> 00:54:35,433
So what part of the judgment
is relevant to this case?

918
00:54:35,503 --> 00:54:39,972
A-Again, i-it's just
the vibe of it.

919
00:54:42,057 --> 00:54:45,021
Actually, may I
approach the bench?

920
00:54:52,607 --> 00:54:55,092
Am I wasting
my time here?

921
00:54:55,165 --> 00:54:57,400
Your case
is not strong.

922
00:54:57,467 --> 00:55:01,173
- Am I sort of in the ballpark though?
- I'm a judge.

923
00:55:01,239 --> 00:55:03,888
I understand.
Can you just give me an angle?

924
00:55:03,957 --> 00:55:06,288
I'm sorry, Mr. Denuto.
I can't.

925
00:55:06,355 --> 00:55:08,425
Understood.
Understood.

926
00:55:08,497 --> 00:55:11,080
I think I've got
a good one anyway.

927
00:55:17,640 --> 00:55:21,467
In summing up,
i-it's the Constitution,

928
00:55:21,541 --> 00:55:24,985
it's Mabo,
it's justice, it's law.

929
00:55:25,058 --> 00:55:28,731
It's the vibe,
and, uh--

930
00:55:28,798 --> 00:55:31,218
No, that's it.
It's the vibe.

931
00:55:33,210 --> 00:55:35,249
I rest my case.

932
00:55:36,280 --> 00:55:38,187
That was sensational.

933
00:55:38,262 --> 00:55:40,497
Counsel for the respondent?

934
00:55:41,874 --> 00:55:44,327
Your Honor, I don't wish to waste
any more of your time.

935
00:55:44,400 --> 00:55:47,693
- Appreciated.
- All our arguments are contained
in the forward documents,

936
00:55:47,758 --> 00:55:51,333
and we'd be more than happy
for that to constitute
the case for the respondent.

937
00:55:51,401 --> 00:55:53,538
Thank you. So be it.

938
00:55:53,608 --> 00:55:55,940
I call a one-hour
adjournment.

939
00:55:56,006 --> 00:55:58,873
Good on ya, Dennis.
That shut 'em up.

940
00:55:58,947 --> 00:56:01,846
I'm going for a bit
of a breather, mate.

941
00:56:41,883 --> 00:56:43,736
How you goin'?

942
00:56:43,802 --> 00:56:45,839
Oh, fine. Fine.

943
00:56:45,912 --> 00:56:48,299
- Got a case comin' up?
- Uh, no, no.

944
00:56:48,374 --> 00:56:51,186
I'm here to see someone.
I'm-I'm a spectator today.

945
00:56:51,251 --> 00:56:54,958
- Are you?
- My son's first appearance.

946
00:56:55,024 --> 00:56:58,534
Oh? Do you reckon
he'll get off?

947
00:56:58,605 --> 00:57:01,023
Oh, no, no.
He's a barrister.

948
00:57:01,099 --> 00:57:04,608
- He's appearing for
the first time as a barrister.
- Congratulations.

949
00:57:04,680 --> 00:57:07,098
- Thank you.
- Uh, Darryl Kerrigan.

950
00:57:07,173 --> 00:57:09,952
- Lawrence Hammill.
- G'day, Lawrence.

951
00:57:10,019 --> 00:57:13,179
Barrister, eh?
He'd need a degree for that.

952
00:57:13,247 --> 00:57:16,561
Yes, yes. He-He's got a couple,
actually.

953
00:57:16,636 --> 00:57:20,593
- Ah, you must be as proud as punch.
- Well, you know.

954
00:57:20,664 --> 00:57:23,029
Oh, I know.
I've got a daughter.

955
00:57:23,094 --> 00:57:26,735
Diploma certificate,
fully qualified hairdresser.

956
00:57:26,803 --> 00:57:30,956
The day she came home
and told me she'd got
into Sunshine Tech...

957
00:57:31,023 --> 00:57:34,315
- was the proudest day of my life.
- Yes, yes, I can imagine.

958
00:57:34,380 --> 00:57:38,239
Yeah, sure makes us parents
look like a bunch of dodos, eh?

959
00:57:39,560 --> 00:57:42,655
You wouldn't have dreamt
of doing what your son's done.

960
00:57:42,724 --> 00:57:46,332
No, no. Anyway, Darryl,
what brings you here?

961
00:57:46,401 --> 00:57:48,820
Our bloody government's
trying to take my house.

962
00:57:48,895 --> 00:57:51,381
This new Air Link thing.
I mean, imagine that.

963
00:57:51,452 --> 00:57:53,938
Sal and me, we brought up
our whole family in that house,

964
00:57:54,011 --> 00:57:56,561
and they think they
can just walk in--

965
00:57:58,006 --> 00:58:00,786
Anyway, we're takin' 'em
to court.

966
00:58:00,852 --> 00:58:04,493
Bloody outrageous.
It's gotta be against the Constitution.

967
00:58:04,561 --> 00:58:07,460
Yes, it is outrageous.
Who's acting for you?

968
00:58:07,534 --> 00:58:11,076
- Dennis Denuto.
- Uh, never heard of him.

969
00:58:11,147 --> 00:58:13,926
You wouldn't have.
He just does our local area.

970
00:58:13,992 --> 00:58:17,120
Yeah, but I've never heard of him
in Constitutional law.

971
00:58:17,188 --> 00:58:20,001
Oh, no, you wouldn't.
No, he does conveyancing mainly.

972
00:58:20,066 --> 00:58:22,485
You know, wills, petty theft,
that sort of thing.

973
00:58:22,560 --> 00:58:24,947
But hey, it's all based
on the Constitution.

974
00:58:25,021 --> 00:58:28,367
Yes. Yes, in a way.

975
00:58:28,444 --> 00:58:32,052
- Good bloke though.
- Yes. Sounds like it.

976
00:58:32,120 --> 00:58:34,866
Anyway, uh,
I'd better be going.

977
00:58:34,933 --> 00:58:38,279
- Sure.
- Nice talking to you, Lawrie.

978
00:58:38,353 --> 00:58:40,904
- Nice talking to you, Darryl.
- And good luck with your boy.

979
00:58:40,975 --> 00:58:45,281
Thanks, Darryl.
I hope everything works out.

980
00:58:45,356 --> 00:58:48,201
Ah, yeah, yeah.
I'm pretty confident.

981
00:58:48,265 --> 00:58:50,532
I find in favor
of the respondent.

982
00:58:50,599 --> 00:58:52,507
Yes!

983
00:58:54,692 --> 00:58:56,861
It's them, Darryl.

984
00:58:56,929 --> 00:59:00,090
But we was respondin'
to them.

985
00:59:00,158 --> 00:59:04,049
We lost, Darryl.
I'm sorry.

986
00:59:04,123 --> 00:59:07,251
<i>Dad reckons he must have
sat there for an hour.</i>

987
00:59:07,319 --> 00:59:10,796
<i>He said it was like being kicked
in the guts with the back end of a bus.</i>

988
00:59:10,868 --> 00:59:14,826
<i>Dad had to explain to Farouk
that they had lost.</i>

989
00:59:14,929 --> 00:59:17,959
<i>It was really hard
telling Evonne too.</i>

990
00:59:18,030 --> 00:59:20,841
<i>But the toughest one
was Jack.</i>

991
00:59:26,118 --> 00:59:27,971
<i>Trace and Con
were great though.</i>

992
00:59:29,858 --> 00:59:33,783
Good on you, Dad. You stood up to them.
I'm so proud of you.

993
00:59:33,856 --> 00:59:37,300
I'm so impressed with your fighting
quality, Mr. Kerrigan.

994
00:59:37,372 --> 00:59:39,224
Thanks, mate.

995
00:59:39,290 --> 00:59:42,931
And can I just say how disenchanted
I am with our legal system.

996
00:59:48,274 --> 00:59:51,468
<i>Dad was very quiet
after losing the court case.</i>

997
00:59:51,536 --> 00:59:54,054
<i>I'd never seen him so down.</i>

998
00:59:54,125 --> 00:59:57,438
<i>He even stopped complimenting Mum
on her cooking.</i>

999
00:59:59,752 --> 01:00:01,757
You all right there,
Darryl?

1000
01:00:01,830 --> 01:00:03,683
Yeah.

1001
01:00:07,999 --> 01:00:10,364
Dad?

1002
01:00:10,429 --> 01:00:13,177
Someone's, uh,

1003
01:00:13,243 --> 01:00:15,891
sellin' a telephone box.

1004
01:00:22,706 --> 01:00:25,421
They said no
to an extension.

1005
01:00:26,607 --> 01:00:29,027
Dennis says we've got
to be out in two weeks.

1006
01:00:29,100 --> 01:00:30,953
Two weeks?

1007
01:00:37,957 --> 01:00:40,410
I haven't told Wayne yet.

1008
01:00:42,049 --> 01:00:44,730
<i>I think Dad felt he'd let
everyone down, but especially Wayne.</i>

1009
01:00:44,798 --> 01:00:47,611
<i>That's why he'd been
puttin' off tellin' him.</i>

1010
01:00:47,676 --> 01:00:50,521
<i>He just couldn't think of a way
to break it to Wayne.</i>

1011
01:00:50,586 --> 01:00:53,582
<i>I told Dad not to worry.
I knew how to tell Wayne we'd lost.</i>

1012
01:00:53,654 --> 01:00:57,164
- We lost.
- Lost?

1013
01:00:57,235 --> 01:00:59,884
Yeah.

1014
01:00:59,953 --> 01:01:01,806
Did Dad do his nut?

1015
01:01:01,870 --> 01:01:04,967
Nah, he's gone all quiet.

1016
01:01:06,123 --> 01:01:08,609
Quiet?

1017
01:01:08,680 --> 01:01:11,874
Yeah. I think he thinks
he's let everyone down.

1018
01:01:11,942 --> 01:01:13,795
Letus down?

1019
01:01:13,861 --> 01:01:16,509
Yeah, that's what I think.

1020
01:01:16,577 --> 01:01:18,430
See, especially you.

1021
01:01:18,496 --> 01:01:21,689
I think he was lookin' forward
to the day you came back to the house.

1022
01:01:21,757 --> 01:01:24,089
Well, you tell Dad...

1023
01:01:24,155 --> 01:01:27,763
the only reason
I loved that house is 'cause
it had him and Mum in it...

1024
01:01:27,831 --> 01:01:30,611
and like... everyone else.

1025
01:01:30,677 --> 01:01:33,228
Wherever they go,
I'll love...

1026
01:01:33,299 --> 01:01:36,591
as long as it
has them in it.

1027
01:01:36,655 --> 01:01:40,842
And all those lawyers
and government people
can just go and get fucked.

1028
01:01:40,908 --> 01:01:42,761
"...as long as it
has them in it.

1029
01:01:42,826 --> 01:01:46,052
And all those lawyers
and government people
can go and get fucked."

1030
01:01:46,119 --> 01:01:50,174
Ah, he wanted me to change
that " get fucked" bit, but I forgot.

1031
01:01:50,243 --> 01:01:52,891
On you, mate.

1032
01:01:52,960 --> 01:01:55,445
I'd better keep packin'.

1033
01:02:32,444 --> 01:02:35,889
Dad?

1034
01:02:35,961 --> 01:02:38,381
Steven.

1035
01:02:38,455 --> 01:02:43,121
I can, uh, get you
some more boxes, if you want.

1036
01:02:43,186 --> 01:02:45,901
No, I think I'll be all right,
Steve.

1037
01:02:50,443 --> 01:02:52,296
Dad?

1038
01:02:54,472 --> 01:02:56,642
You haven't let anyone down.

1039
01:02:58,117 --> 01:03:01,726
I don't know what the opposite of...
lettin' someone down is,

1040
01:03:03,553 --> 01:03:05,884
but you done
the opposite.

1041
01:03:18,707 --> 01:03:21,071
When are you
gonna sign 'em?

1042
01:03:23,214 --> 01:03:26,310
- I don't know.
- They gotta be done by Friday.

1043
01:03:26,380 --> 01:03:28,995
I can't.

1044
01:03:29,065 --> 01:03:31,070
lcan't.
I just can't.

1045
01:03:31,142 --> 01:03:33,508
Darryl, we gotta go.

1046
01:03:33,573 --> 01:03:35,546
Yeah, I know.
I know we lost.

1047
01:03:35,619 --> 01:03:37,950
I know we gotta get out
of this place.

1048
01:03:38,017 --> 01:03:41,788
I know this is no longer
our house, but I'll be buggered
if I can sign those papers.

1049
01:03:41,853 --> 01:03:45,625
I just cannot physically
pick up the pen and sign them.

1050
01:03:50,421 --> 01:03:52,427
Did you speak
to Jack?

1051
01:03:52,500 --> 01:03:57,034
Yeah, yeah. His son-in-law's moved
to Perth, so he's no help.

1052
01:03:57,104 --> 01:04:00,362
Poor Jack.

1053
01:04:00,428 --> 01:04:04,320
Listen, I-I told him
he could stay with us
until we work somethin' out.

1054
01:04:05,927 --> 01:04:08,064
How'd you go
with the agent?

1055
01:04:08,133 --> 01:04:11,196
Two-bedroom units
are $80,000.

1056
01:04:11,266 --> 01:04:13,119
A flat.

1057
01:04:13,184 --> 01:04:16,564
With four people,
the greyhounds,

1058
01:04:16,638 --> 01:04:18,872
five cars,

1059
01:04:18,939 --> 01:04:20,847
the boat and Jack.

1060
01:04:20,922 --> 01:04:22,927
It'll be okay.

1061
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:26,825
- And what are we gonna do with Wayne?
- Wayne'll understand.

1062
01:04:26,900 --> 01:04:30,160
You know he keeps a photo
of this place on his wall.

1063
01:04:30,226 --> 01:04:32,079
I know.

1064
01:04:32,144 --> 01:04:37,190
He gets out after five years,
we have to put him in a laundry
smaller than his cell.

1065
01:04:37,258 --> 01:04:40,605
- Maybe we rent.
- Rent?

1066
01:04:40,680 --> 01:04:43,906
We not only lose our place,
we're payin' for someone else's.

1067
01:04:43,972 --> 01:04:47,897
- Oh, Darryl--
- I'm starting to understand
how the aborigines feel.

1068
01:04:50,364 --> 01:04:52,852
Have you been drinkin'?

1069
01:04:52,924 --> 01:04:55,707
Well, this house
is like their land.

1070
01:04:55,773 --> 01:04:57,879
It-It holds
their memories.

1071
01:04:57,950 --> 01:05:00,284
The land is their story.
It's everything.

1072
01:05:00,350 --> 01:05:04,126
You just can't pick it up
and plonk it down somewhere else.

1073
01:05:05,534 --> 01:05:08,830
This country's gotta stop
stealin' other people's land.

1074
01:05:08,895 --> 01:05:12,279
Dad? There's someone
here to see you.

1075
01:05:14,240 --> 01:05:16,096
G'day, Darryl.

1076
01:05:17,217 --> 01:05:19,073
Lawrie.

1077
01:05:20,163 --> 01:05:22,335
So I thought
I'd come and visit.

1078
01:05:22,404 --> 01:05:25,274
- But how'd you find us?
- You know us dodos.

1079
01:05:25,347 --> 01:05:28,251
- We've got a few tricks up our sleeves.
- Don't I know it.

1080
01:05:29,317 --> 01:05:32,481
I, uh, heard
about the decision.

1081
01:05:32,550 --> 01:05:35,747
Yeah. Yeah, well,
that's the way these things are.

1082
01:05:35,814 --> 01:05:38,367
- How'd your boy go?
- Oh, fine. Yeah, fine.

1083
01:05:38,438 --> 01:05:42,150
- Great.
- Darryl, I wonder if I
could put something to you.

1084
01:05:42,217 --> 01:05:44,072
Yeah, sure.

1085
01:05:44,137 --> 01:05:47,006
I don't think I
introduced myself fully.

1086
01:05:47,080 --> 01:05:50,725
You see, I'm retired now,
but I'm actually a lawyer myself.

1087
01:05:50,795 --> 01:05:54,984
Three degrees in the family.
I'd like to see your poolroom.

1088
01:05:55,050 --> 01:05:57,987
I'm, uh,
what's called a Q.C.

1089
01:05:58,060 --> 01:06:01,158
- Are you? A Q.C.? You're one of those?
- What's that?

1090
01:06:01,229 --> 01:06:04,677
- Uh, Queens Counsel.
- Oh, you counsel the queen?

1091
01:06:04,749 --> 01:06:07,881
Uh, they're the lawyers
rich people use, love.

1092
01:06:07,949 --> 01:06:11,300
Yeah, well, that's probably
the most accurate way of describing us.

1093
01:06:11,375 --> 01:06:13,285
I don't think Dennis
would be a Q.C.

1094
01:06:13,359 --> 01:06:17,102
N-No, no, I don't think.

1095
01:06:17,168 --> 01:06:19,503
Anyway, my specialty
as a Q.C...

1096
01:06:19,570 --> 01:06:22,472
was Constitutional law,
Australian Constitutional law.

1097
01:06:22,546 --> 01:06:25,067
Have you heard of
the Tasmanian Dams case?

1098
01:06:26,258 --> 01:06:28,495
- Um--
- Mabo?

1099
01:06:28,564 --> 01:06:31,794
Oh, the aboriginal guy,
told the government to shove it.

1100
01:06:31,860 --> 01:06:33,715
That's the one.

1101
01:06:33,780 --> 01:06:37,457
Uh, anyway, I've had quite
a bit to do with these over the years,

1102
01:06:37,524 --> 01:06:41,139
and I've had a look into your case
over the last few days,

1103
01:06:41,206 --> 01:06:43,694
and I think there's
a bit more to it.

1104
01:06:43,768 --> 01:06:47,063
- What do you mean?
- I think you've got a case.

1105
01:06:47,127 --> 01:06:50,194
- So Dennis was on the right track.
- Y-Yes.

1106
01:06:50,264 --> 01:06:52,239
I told you that judge
had it in for him.

1107
01:06:52,313 --> 01:06:54,583
I believe there's a section
of the Constitution...

1108
01:06:54,649 --> 01:06:57,879
about the government's right to acquire
land that hasn't been tested.

1109
01:06:57,946 --> 01:07:00,019
But Dennis tested it.

1110
01:07:00,090 --> 01:07:03,954
Well, I-I think we
could test it better.

1111
01:07:04,028 --> 01:07:08,120
Anyway, I would like
to appear on your behalf... gratis.

1112
01:07:09,277 --> 01:07:12,408
- No fee.
- Well, no, we couldn't.

1113
01:07:12,479 --> 01:07:14,899
I've done pretty well
out of this law caper over the years,

1114
01:07:14,974 --> 01:07:17,844
- so if you're happy for me
to take it further--
-Further?

1115
01:07:17,919 --> 01:07:20,919
But we've been
to the federal court.

1116
01:07:20,991 --> 01:07:23,327
How much further
can we take it?

1117
01:07:23,424 --> 01:07:25,247
<i>Three weeks later...</i>

1118
01:07:25,312 --> 01:07:29,307
<i>Dad went to the High Court
of Australia, which is the
highest court in Australia.</i>

1119
01:07:29,378 --> 01:07:32,280
<i>Lawrie asked Dennis to be
his instructing solicitor.</i>

1120
01:07:32,354 --> 01:07:35,584
<i>Dennis was stoked,
but shittin' himself at the same time.</i>

1121
01:07:35,651 --> 01:07:38,041
I'm shittin' myself.

1122
01:07:38,116 --> 01:07:41,979
- Shall we?
- Let's stick it up 'em.

1123
01:07:44,518 --> 01:07:46,852
<i>And so Dad, or as he
was called by the judge--</i>

1124
01:07:46,917 --> 01:07:49,668
<i>Darryl John Kerrigan--</i>

1125
01:07:49,734 --> 01:07:51,971
<i>sat in the High Court
of Australia and put his case.</i>

1126
01:07:52,039 --> 01:07:54,212
<i>Or at least
Mr. Hammill did.</i>

1127
01:07:54,281 --> 01:07:58,559
<i>Dennis was very helpful too.
He was passing books around
like a librarian.</i>

1128
01:07:58,633 --> 01:08:01,666
<i>He even learnt Roman numerals
especially for the trip.</i>

1129
01:08:01,737 --> 01:08:05,733
Um, paragraph, uh... 31.

1130
01:08:05,803 --> 01:08:09,001
- Thank you, Dennis.
- But Dad reckoned there
was no doubt about it.

1131
01:08:09,068 --> 01:08:12,199
<i>From the moment he stood up,
Mr. Hammill was the star of the show.</i>

1132
01:08:12,268 --> 01:08:15,815
Section 51,
paragraph 31.

1133
01:08:15,886 --> 01:08:18,734
"The parliament shall
have power to make laws...

1134
01:08:18,798 --> 01:08:23,818
with respect to the acquisition
of property on just terms."

1135
01:08:23,887 --> 01:08:26,757
Let's think about those words,
"on just terms" ...

1136
01:08:26,831 --> 01:08:29,417
and how they relate
to real people.

1137
01:08:29,489 --> 01:08:31,878
Your Honor, my client
built his home by the law,

1138
01:08:31,952 --> 01:08:34,604
in full accordance
with the law.

1139
01:08:34,673 --> 01:08:37,063
He doesn't know
about the extensions.

1140
01:08:37,139 --> 01:08:39,278
But does he have
the protection of the law?

1141
01:08:39,347 --> 01:08:43,603
How can the forcible removal
of a family, a good family,
from their home...

1142
01:08:43,668 --> 01:08:46,668
have the blessing
of our Constitution?

1143
01:08:46,740 --> 01:08:49,971
How can that be...
"just terms" ?

1144
01:08:50,037 --> 01:08:52,142
<i>Dad reckoned it
was in the bag,</i>

1145
01:08:52,213 --> 01:08:55,924
<i>even though they had five times
more lawyers than we did.</i>

1146
01:08:55,990 --> 01:08:58,806
My client has adhered
to the law, every law,

1147
01:08:58,871 --> 01:09:02,800
every statute from the Town Planning Act
to Civil Aviation Regulations.

1148
01:09:02,872 --> 01:09:06,036
But in what can only be described
as a last desperate measure,

1149
01:09:06,104 --> 01:09:10,328
my client is accused
of breaching none other
than the Constitution.

1150
01:09:10,393 --> 01:09:13,329
I mean, good Lord,
what else are we guilty of?

1151
01:09:13,403 --> 01:09:16,306
lnternational war crimes, hmm?

1152
01:09:16,380 --> 01:09:18,998
He's even paid people
to laugh for him.

1153
01:09:19,068 --> 01:09:22,364
I refer the court to His Honor
Mr. Justice Dixon's decision...

1154
01:09:22,429 --> 01:09:24,284
in Grace Brothers
and the Commonwealth.

1155
01:09:24,349 --> 01:09:27,514
<i>As much as Dad hated to admit
it the other lawyer was good,</i>

1156
01:09:27,582 --> 01:09:30,168
<i>and he was gonna give us
a real run for our money.</i>

1157
01:09:30,239 --> 01:09:32,094
A safeguard
to the commonwealth.

1158
01:09:32,160 --> 01:09:36,161
<i>But if Mr. Hammill was worried,
he didn't show it. He kept right on at 'em.</i>

1159
01:09:36,162 --> 01:09:38,550
...has acquired the status
of a constitutional guarantee,

1160
01:09:38,626 --> 01:09:40,730
which is designed
to protect the individual--

1161
01:09:40,802 --> 01:09:43,355
<i>But everything he said,
they had an answer for.</i>

1162
01:09:43,426 --> 01:09:46,841
- Your Honor, that statement
was obiter dictum.
- Was not!

1163
01:09:50,019 --> 01:09:52,322
Well, it wasn't.

1164
01:09:52,389 --> 01:09:54,560
- Was it?
- I don't know.

1165
01:09:54,628 --> 01:09:58,720
The interpretation of
"on just terms" was considered
in the Tasmanian Dams case.

1166
01:09:58,790 --> 01:10:02,817
The court took into account
the interests of the community,

1167
01:10:02,887 --> 01:10:05,822
such as, uh,
job creation--

1168
01:10:05,895 --> 01:10:08,416
<i>Dad reckoned Dennis got
the hang of things real quick.</i>

1169
01:10:08,488 --> 01:10:12,711
<i>The main job of the senior counsel
was to provide backup for the Q.C.</i>

1170
01:10:12,776 --> 01:10:16,355
Ah, yes. And this is further underlined
in Georgiades--

1171
01:10:16,426 --> 01:10:19,656
- And that's what Dennis did.
- Ah, utilitarianism.

1172
01:10:19,723 --> 01:10:22,473
The greatest good
for the greatest number.

1173
01:10:22,540 --> 01:10:25,410
But what this principle
fails to--

1174
01:10:31,790 --> 01:10:34,572
What this principle fails to take
into account...

1175
01:10:34,638 --> 01:10:38,502
is that competing rights cannot
be weighed one against the other.

1176
01:10:38,576 --> 01:10:42,025
Is a family's right to live freely
in their home outweighed--

1177
01:10:42,096 --> 01:10:44,333
<i>It wasn't just
legal argument.</i>

1178
01:10:44,400 --> 01:10:47,020
<i>Mr. Hammill even put jokes in,
clever jokes.</i>

1179
01:10:47,090 --> 01:10:50,505
...not that our children
will have a place to live,

1180
01:10:50,578 --> 01:10:54,539
but whether they'll have prompt delivery
of their parcels.

1181
01:10:54,611 --> 01:10:57,262
<i>Dad thought
it was real funny,</i>

1182
01:10:57,332 --> 01:10:59,536
<i>even though he
didn't get it.</i>

1183
01:10:59,605 --> 01:11:02,605
Suffer in your jocks.

1184
01:11:02,678 --> 01:11:06,672
<i>In fact, there were
a lot of times he didn't quite
understand what was being said,</i>

1185
01:11:06,741 --> 01:11:10,486
<i>but one time he knew exactly
what was being said.</i>

1186
01:11:10,552 --> 01:11:13,781
He's even approached
the appellant with an offer
of compensation,

1187
01:11:13,848 --> 01:11:18,389
a generous offer considering
the nature of the, uh, dwelling,

1188
01:11:18,458 --> 01:11:21,425
or as it might more accurately
be called, eyesore.

1189
01:11:21,497 --> 01:11:24,084
- What are you calling an eyesore?
- Darryl.

1190
01:11:24,155 --> 01:11:26,392
It's called a home,
you dickhead!

1191
01:11:26,459 --> 01:11:28,314
- Your Honor.
- Darryl!

1192
01:11:28,379 --> 01:11:31,226
It's a bloody fine one. If there
were more homes like that, we'd--

1193
01:11:31,292 --> 01:11:34,010
Have the jails full
of people like your son?

1194
01:11:34,076 --> 01:11:36,946
- Ah, this bloody asshole!
- Sit down, Darryl.

1195
01:11:37,021 --> 01:11:39,542
Mr. Hammill, I'm calling
an adjournment.

1196
01:11:39,614 --> 01:11:44,351
And I trust that your client
will, in the meantime, compose himself.

1197
01:11:44,416 --> 01:11:49,567
Mr. Lyle, I'll thank you
not to make any further value
judgments in this court.

1198
01:11:49,633 --> 01:11:51,576
I'm sorry, Lawrie.

1199
01:11:51,649 --> 01:11:53,559
That's all right, Darryl.

1200
01:11:53,633 --> 01:11:55,575
I was thinking
the same thing,

1201
01:11:55,651 --> 01:11:58,138
though not
in those words.

1202
01:11:58,210 --> 01:12:01,113
I wish I had your words.

1203
01:12:01,188 --> 01:12:03,043
How dare they?

1204
01:12:03,108 --> 01:12:04,963
I mean, an eyesore!

1205
01:12:05,028 --> 01:12:08,258
I mean, that--
that just goes to show
that they don't get it.

1206
01:12:08,325 --> 01:12:10,660
I mean, they're judging the place
by what it looks like,

1207
01:12:10,725 --> 01:12:15,615
and if it doesn't have
a pool or a classy front
or a big garden--

1208
01:12:15,687 --> 01:12:17,694
It's got a pretty good gate.

1209
01:12:17,768 --> 01:12:21,795
And then because of that,
it's not worth saving.

1210
01:12:21,865 --> 01:12:25,444
But it's not a house.
It's a home.

1211
01:12:25,513 --> 01:12:28,002
It's got everything.

1212
01:12:28,074 --> 01:12:31,620
People who love each other,
care for each other.

1213
01:12:31,690 --> 01:12:33,633
It's got memories.

1214
01:12:33,707 --> 01:12:35,650
Great memories.

1215
01:12:35,725 --> 01:12:39,467
It's a place
for the family to turn to,

1216
01:12:39,532 --> 01:12:42,021
come back to.

1217
01:12:42,093 --> 01:12:46,666
But that doesn't seem to mean as much
as a big fuckin' driveway.

1218
01:12:46,734 --> 01:12:49,802
<i>Later it was time
for Mr. Hammill to sum up.</i>

1219
01:12:49,872 --> 01:12:53,221
<i>Dad said
he was unbelievable.</i>

1220
01:12:53,296 --> 01:12:56,230
<i>He reckoned he finished
like a champion greyhound.</i>

1221
01:12:56,304 --> 01:12:57,650
People who love each other--

1222
01:12:57,651 --> 01:13:00,284
<i>He quoted cases, he quoted laws.</i>

1223
01:13:00,543 --> 01:13:04,267
<i>But Dad nearly fell off
his chair when Mr. Hammill
finished by quoting Dad,</i>

1224
01:13:04,338 --> 01:13:06,193
<i>only better.</i>

1225
01:13:06,258 --> 01:13:09,455
And somehow that's not worth
as much as a big driveway.

1226
01:13:09,524 --> 01:13:14,413
You may think our appeal
is based on emotion rather than law.

1227
01:13:14,485 --> 01:13:16,526
Not true.

1228
01:13:16,598 --> 01:13:20,689
It's about the highest law in
this country, the Constitution,

1229
01:13:20,759 --> 01:13:24,372
and one phrase within it:
"on just terms."

1230
01:13:26,905 --> 01:13:30,221
That's what this
is all about-- being just.

1231
01:13:30,296 --> 01:13:33,713
They want to pay only
for the house.

1232
01:13:33,785 --> 01:13:37,616
But they're taking away
more than that, so much more.

1233
01:13:37,691 --> 01:13:40,823
Sure, the Kerrigans
built a house,

1234
01:13:40,892 --> 01:13:43,543
then they built a home,
and then a family.

1235
01:13:43,612 --> 01:13:47,836
You can acquire a house,

1236
01:13:47,901 --> 01:13:50,584
but you can't
acquire a home,

1237
01:13:50,654 --> 01:13:53,338
because a home is not built
of bricks and mortar...

1238
01:13:53,406 --> 01:13:56,953
but love and memories.

1239
01:13:58,209 --> 01:14:00,347
You can't pay for it,

1240
01:14:00,416 --> 01:14:03,319
and you're just shortchanging
people if you try.

1241
01:14:03,393 --> 01:14:07,671
I can't speak for those
who wrote this document,

1242
01:14:07,746 --> 01:14:11,359
but I'll bet when they put in
the phrase " on just terms,"

1243
01:14:11,426 --> 01:14:14,724
they hoped
it would stop anyone...

1244
01:14:14,788 --> 01:14:19,196
shortchanging someone
like Darryl Kerrigan.

1245
01:14:21,254 --> 01:14:23,872
Thanks, Lawrence.

1246
01:14:29,863 --> 01:14:32,963
Thank you.

1247
01:14:33,031 --> 01:14:37,115
<i>In the end, who knows whether
it was Dad's words or Mr. Hammill</i>

1248
01:14:37,116 --> 01:14:40,563
<i>or even Dennis' note passing--
...but we won the case.</i>

1249
01:14:40,731 --> 01:14:42,593
...in favor
of the appellant.

1250
01:14:42,666 --> 01:14:44,521
Shit.

1251
01:14:46,220 --> 01:14:48,075
That's us.

1252
01:14:48,140 --> 01:14:50,824
Bullshit.
We won?

1253
01:14:50,892 --> 01:14:54,275
- We won.
- You little ripper!

1254
01:14:54,349 --> 01:14:58,245
Thanks, lads.

1255
01:14:58,318 --> 01:14:59,079
We won.

1256
01:14:59,080 --> 01:15:01,682
<i>Dad was stoked
but suitably restrained.</i>

1257
01:15:01,775 --> 01:15:04,645
<i>He reckons the other side
didn't know what to do with themselves.</i>

1258
01:15:04,718 --> 01:15:07,141
<i>Dennis was so stunned,
he went all quiet.</i>

1259
01:15:07,216 --> 01:15:10,762
<i>Dad reckons he almost cried.
In fact, I think he did.</i>

1260
01:15:10,833 --> 01:15:13,354
<i>Mr. Hammill
just sat there for ages.</i>

1261
01:15:13,426 --> 01:15:17,681
<i>He reckoned it was the most satisfying
victory he'd had in 47 years.</i>

1262
01:15:17,747 --> 01:15:21,425
<i>Dad reckons it's important
to be noble in victory,
so he spoke to the other Q.C. ...</i>

1263
01:15:21,491 --> 01:15:22,518
Oh, hey.

1264
01:15:22,519 --> 01:15:24,150
<i>...the one who had a go at Wayne.</i>

1265
01:15:24,293 --> 01:15:26,609
Bad luck.

1266
01:15:26,676 --> 01:15:29,744
You dickhead!

1267
01:15:30,869 --> 01:15:34,253
<i>The case was all over
the news that night.</i>

1268
01:15:34,359 --> 01:15:38,255
Good evening. First tonight,
a landmark decision in
the High Court today...

1269
01:15:38,328 --> 01:15:41,776
has confirmed the age-old saying,
"A man's home is his castle."

1270
01:15:41,849 --> 01:15:46,127
When the huge Air Link
consortium tried to compulsorily
acquire a string of homes...

1271
01:15:46,202 --> 01:15:48,591
on Melbourne's outskirts
earlier this year,

1272
01:15:48,666 --> 01:15:50,936
they didn't expect a fight.

1273
01:15:51,003 --> 01:15:54,452
- Well, they got one.
- It was a
case of Darryl versus Goliath...

1274
01:15:54,523 --> 01:15:56,858
in the High Court
of Australia today.

1275
01:15:56,924 --> 01:15:59,959
<i>Mum reckons it's real funny
how one day you're not famous,</i>

1276
01:16:00,029 --> 01:16:02,102
<i>and then the next day
you are... famous,</i>

1277
01:16:02,173 --> 01:16:04,028
<i>and then you're not
anymore.</i>

1278
01:16:04,093 --> 01:16:08,569
<i>Dad had one of the biggest parties ever
that night back at home.</i>

1279
01:16:08,639 --> 01:16:11,061
<i>He invited everyone
from the neighborhood--</i>

1280
01:16:11,136 --> 01:16:13,110
<i>his friends,
family, in-laws.</i>

1281
01:16:13,185 --> 01:16:16,250
This case has totally regained my faith
in the legal system.

1282
01:16:16,321 --> 01:16:18,150
<i>Mr. Hammill even
brought his son along.</i>

1283
01:16:18,151 --> 01:16:19,993
Really pleased to meet you.

1284
01:16:20,098 --> 01:16:22,619
<i>Everyone was havin'
a real good time,</i>

1285
01:16:26,402 --> 01:16:28,641
<i>especially Mum and Dad.</i>

1286
01:16:28,709 --> 01:16:31,905
<i>I'd never seen them
so happy.</i>

1287
01:16:31,973 --> 01:16:34,144
<i>Dad invited everyone
up to Bonnie Doon.</i>

1288
01:16:34,213 --> 01:16:36,385
I fix for you a special Farouk
pressure system.

1289
01:16:36,453 --> 01:16:40,000
<i>Mr. Hammill said he'd love
to come. I don't think he'd
ever fished for carp.</i>

1290
01:16:40,070 --> 01:16:44,350
<i>Well, that party
went on and on and on.
Dad smiled all night.</i>

1291
01:16:44,489 --> 01:16:46,565
See, this is why we need that patio.

1292
01:16:46,631 --> 01:16:48,869
<i>The victory was reported
in all the papers.</i>

1293
01:16:48,936 --> 01:16:51,752
<i>It became known
as the Kerrigan Decision.</i>

1294
01:16:51,817 --> 01:16:53,825
Jack, don't thank me.
This is the bloke.

1295
01:16:53,898 --> 01:16:57,281
<i>Although Dad said,
as far as he was concerned,
it was Lawrie's victory.</i>

1296
01:16:57,355 --> 01:17:00,323
And don't forget
Dennis here either.

1297
01:17:00,396 --> 01:17:03,745
<i>That was the beginning
of a string of good luck
for our family.</i>

1298
01:17:03,820 --> 01:17:08,163
<i>Six months later
we got notice that Wayne would
soon be eligible for parole.</i>

1299
01:17:08,237 --> 01:17:12,100
<i>Dad rang Mr. Hammill,
who was more than happy
to come out of retirement again.</i>

1300
01:17:12,174 --> 01:17:14,892
<i>Wayne said the parole board
couldn't believe their eyes.</i>

1301
01:17:14,958 --> 01:17:18,342
<i>When Mr. Hammill walked in,
he reckons they granted him
parole out of shock.</i>

1302
01:17:20,336 --> 01:17:22,857
<i>Dennis became very well-known
after the case,</i>

1303
01:17:22,928 --> 01:17:25,297
<i>and people came from everywhere
to hire him.</i>

1304
01:17:25,362 --> 01:17:27,217
<i>He won a very big case,</i>

1305
01:17:27,282 --> 01:17:31,178
<i>a class action against people who put
lead in the landfill 15 years ago.</i>

1306
01:17:31,250 --> 01:17:34,569
<i>I think Mr. Hammill
helped him there too.
Dad is very happy for him.</i>

1307
01:17:34,644 --> 01:17:37,776
<i>He even bought himself
a new photocopier,</i>

1308
01:17:37,845 --> 01:17:40,333
<i>one that never breaks down.</i>

1309
01:17:40,405 --> 01:17:43,754
<i>And guess what. Mr. Hammill did go up
to Bonnie Doon.</i>

1310
01:17:43,829 --> 01:17:46,897
<i>At first Dad thought it was
out of politeness, but it can't be...</i>

1311
01:17:46,966 --> 01:17:49,203
<i>'cause he goes up there
all the time.</i>

1312
01:17:49,272 --> 01:17:53,266
<i>He and Dad still hit it off
as good as they did
the first day they met.</i>

1313
01:17:53,336 --> 01:17:55,442
<i>Coco never won another race,</i>

1314
01:17:55,513 --> 01:17:58,513
<i>but she had a son
which Dad called Son of Coco.</i>

1315
01:17:58,585 --> 01:18:01,455
<i>He hasn't won yet,
but Dad has high hopes.</i>

1316
01:18:01,531 --> 01:18:05,687
<i>Dad did finish the patio
in a Greek style, and the extension,</i>

1317
01:18:05,755 --> 01:18:08,275
<i>and he even put up those big iron gates
that he and Steve...</i>

1318
01:18:08,347 --> 01:18:10,934
<i>had gotten for a bargain
that night in Toorak.</i>

1319
01:18:11,004 --> 01:18:13,306
<i>Steve got back with Kerry,
his old girlfriend.</i>

1320
01:18:13,373 --> 01:18:16,985
<i>Eventually they got married
and had a little boy...
three weeks later.</i>

1321
01:18:17,055 --> 01:18:20,055
"Baby carriage,
still in box."

1322
01:18:20,126 --> 01:18:22,266
<i>Con and Trace
had a kid too.</i>

1323
01:18:22,335 --> 01:18:26,773
<i>He's already taken up kickboxing.
They are great parents.</i>

1324
01:18:27,809 --> 01:18:31,606
<i>Wayne started helping Dad
with the tow truck
and really made a go at it.</i>

1325
01:18:31,680 --> 01:18:35,227
<i>Dad's even more proud of him now
than when he was in jail.</i>

1326
01:18:35,299 --> 01:18:37,404
<i>It was Wayne's idea
to move into tray trucks.</i>

1327
01:18:37,475 --> 01:18:40,062
<i>Pretty soon they had two,
